# BILLING AND PRICING — Difficulty 1
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
questions += [
  {"question_text":"What are the three types of AWS Free Tier offers?","options":["Basic, Standard, Premium","Always Free, 12 Months Free, Trials","Free, Discounted, Paid","Starter, Developer, Enterprise"],"correct_answer":"Always Free, 12 Months Free, Trials","explanation":"Always Free offers never expire. 12 Months Free offers are available for the first 12 months after account creation. Trials are short-term free offers for specific services.","memory_technique":"Always, 12 months, Trials — A12T. Always available, 12-month honeymoon, short trials.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":1,"it_context_mapping":"The Free Tier is like a vendor proof-of-concept environment — limited access to evaluate services before committing budget."},
  {"question_text":"What is an On-Demand EC2 instance?","options":["An instance you reserve for 1 or 3 years","An instance that uses spare capacity and can be interrupted","An instance you pay for by the hour or second with no commitment","A dedicated physical server"],"correct_answer":"An instance you pay for by the hour or second with no commitment","explanation":"On-Demand instances let you pay for compute capacity by the hour or second with no long-term commitments or upfront payments. Ideal for unpredictable workloads.","memory_technique":"On-Demand = On your demand, when you want it. Like a taxi — pay per ride, no contract.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":1,"it_context_mapping":"On-Demand is equivalent to renting servers by the hour from a hosting provider — no commitment, highest flexibility, highest per-unit cost."},
  {"question_text":"What is a Reserved Instance?","options":["An instance that is reserved for emergency use","An EC2 pricing option offering discounts in exchange for a 1 or 3-year commitment","An instance that cannot be terminated","A spot instance with guaranteed availability"],"correct_answer":"An EC2 pricing option offering discounts in exchange for a 1 or 3-year commitment","explanation":"Reserved Instances provide significant discounts (up to 72%) compared to On-Demand pricing in exchange for committing to a specific instance type for 1 or 3 years.","memory_technique":"Reserved = Reserved seat on a plane. Commit to the seat (1 or 3 years) and get a cheaper ticket.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":1,"it_context_mapping":"Reserved Instances are like a 1 or 3-year server lease vs. month-to-month hosting. The commitment gives you a lower rate."},
  {"question_text":"What is a Spot Instance?","options":["An instance reserved for specific time slots","An EC2 instance that uses spare capacity at up to 90% discount but can be interrupted","An instance with guaranteed uptime","A dedicated physical server"],"correct_answer":"An EC2 instance that uses spare capacity at up to 90% discount but can be interrupted","explanation":"Spot Instances use spare EC2 capacity and can offer discounts of up to 90% compared to On-Demand prices. AWS can reclaim Spot Instances with a 2-minute warning.","memory_technique":"Spot = Spot price at an auction. Cheap when supply is high, but the auctioneer can take it back.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":1,"it_context_mapping":"Spot Instances are like standby airline tickets — huge discount, but you might get bumped. Ideal for fault-tolerant batch jobs."},
  {"question_text":"What tool would you use to estimate the cost of a new AWS architecture before deploying it?","options":["AWS Cost Explorer","AWS Budgets","AWS Pricing Calculator","AWS Trusted Advisor"],"correct_answer":"AWS Pricing Calculator","explanation":"The AWS Pricing Calculator lets you explore AWS services and create an estimate for the cost of your use cases before deploying anything.","memory_technique":"Pricing Calculator = Price tag before you buy. Like getting a quote from a contractor before starting construction.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":1,"it_context_mapping":"The Pricing Calculator replaces the manual process of requesting quotes from hardware vendors. It's a self-service TCO calculator."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Cost Explorer?","options":["A tool for estimating future costs before deployment","A tool for visualising and analysing your AWS cost and usage data over time","A tool for setting spending alerts","A tool for generating compliance reports"],"correct_answer":"A tool for visualising and analysing your AWS cost and usage data over time","explanation":"AWS Cost Explorer provides an interface to visualise, understand, and manage your AWS costs and usage over time, with filtering, grouping, and forecasting capabilities.","memory_technique":"Cost Explorer = Cost GPS. Shows where you've been (historical costs) and where you're heading (forecasts).","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":1,"it_context_mapping":"Cost Explorer is like a financial analytics dashboard applied to your AWS bill — it helps you understand spending patterns and identify optimisation opportunities."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Budgets used for?","options":["Estimating costs before deployment","Setting custom cost and usage alerts","Viewing historical cost data","Managing Reserved Instances"],"correct_answer":"Setting custom cost and usage alerts","explanation":"AWS Budgets allows you to set custom budgets and receive alerts when your costs or usage exceed (or are forecasted to exceed) your budgeted amount.","memory_technique":"Budgets = Budget alarm clock. Set your spending limit and AWS wakes you up when you're about to exceed it.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":1,"it_context_mapping":"AWS Budgets is equivalent to budget alerts in enterprise financial systems — it notifies stakeholders when spending approaches or exceeds approved limits."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Total Cost of Ownership (TCO) Calculator used for?","options":["Calculating the cost of AWS services only","Comparing the cost of running workloads on-premises versus on AWS","Tracking monthly AWS spending","Estimating Reserved Instance savings"],"correct_answer":"Comparing the cost of running workloads on-premises versus on AWS","explanation":"The TCO Calculator (now part of the AWS Pricing Calculator) helps compare the full cost of on-premises infrastructure versus AWS, including hardware, software, facilities, and labour.","memory_technique":"TCO = Total Cost of Ownership. Like comparing the true cost of owning a car vs. using Uber — AWS TCO shows the full picture.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":1,"it_context_mapping":"TCO analysis is a standard IT financial exercise. The AWS TCO Calculator automates what traditionally required a spreadsheet comparing CapEx vs. OpEx."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Consolidated Billing?","options":["A feature that splits bills across multiple accounts","A feature that combines usage from multiple AWS accounts into a single bill","A service for paying AWS invoices","A tool for forecasting future costs"],"correct_answer":"A feature that combines usage from multiple AWS accounts into a single bill","explanation":"Consolidated Billing in AWS Organizations combines usage from all member accounts into a single bill, potentially qualifying for volume discounts and simplifying payment.","memory_technique":"Consolidated = combined into one. Like a family mobile plan — one bill, shared data allowance.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":1,"it_context_mapping":"Consolidated Billing mirrors enterprise software licensing agreements where total company-wide usage determines the discount tier."},
  {"question_text":"Which AWS service provides recommendations to reduce costs, improve performance, and enhance security?","options":["AWS Cost Explorer","AWS Config","AWS Trusted Advisor","AWS Well-Architected Tool"],"correct_answer":"AWS Trusted Advisor","explanation":"AWS Trusted Advisor inspects your AWS environment and provides recommendations across five categories: Cost Optimisation, Performance, Security, Fault Tolerance, and Service Limits.","memory_technique":"Trusted Advisor = Your AWS financial advisor + security consultant + performance engineer in one.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":1,"it_context_mapping":"Trusted Advisor is like an automated IT audit tool — similar to what a consulting firm would provide when reviewing your infrastructure for cost savings and security improvements."},
  {"question_text":"What is a Savings Plan in AWS?","options":["A fixed monthly payment plan for all AWS services","A flexible pricing model offering savings in exchange for a commitment to a consistent amount of compute usage","A plan that saves your AWS configuration settings","A discount for non-profit organisations"],"correct_answer":"A flexible pricing model offering savings in exchange for a commitment to a consistent amount of compute usage","explanation":"Savings Plans offer significant savings (up to 66%) over On-Demand in exchange for committing to a consistent amount of compute usage ($/hour) for 1 or 3 years, applying automatically across EC2, Fargate, and Lambda.","memory_technique":"Savings Plans = Flexible gym membership. Commit to spending $X/hour on compute, get a discount — works across any machine type.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":1,"it_context_mapping":"Savings Plans are more flexible than Reserved Instances — like an enterprise software agreement that covers a portfolio of products rather than a specific SKU."},
]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# CLOUD CONCEPTS — Difficulty 2
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
questions += [
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Shared Responsibility Model?","options":["AWS is responsible for all security","Customers are responsible for all security","AWS is responsible for security OF the cloud; customers are responsible for security IN the cloud","Security is split 50/50"],"correct_answer":"AWS is responsible for security OF the cloud; customers are responsible for security IN the cloud","explanation":"AWS manages security of the underlying infrastructure. Customers manage security of what they put in the cloud — data, applications, IAM, OS configuration.","memory_technique":"OF vs IN: AWS owns the building (OF the cloud), you own what's inside your apartment (IN the cloud).","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Like a colocation data center: the colo provider secures the building and power, but you secure your own servers and data."},
  {"question_text":"Which AWS support plan provides access to a Technical Account Manager (TAM)?","options":["Basic","Developer","Business","Enterprise"],"correct_answer":"Enterprise","explanation":"The Enterprise support plan includes a dedicated Technical Account Manager (TAM) who provides proactive guidance and coordinates access to AWS programs and experts.","memory_technique":"Enterprise = Executive treatment. TAM = Your personal AWS concierge.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"A TAM is similar to a dedicated account manager at a traditional IT vendor like IBM or HP, providing personalised technical guidance."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between vertical scaling and horizontal scaling?","options":["Vertical scaling adds more instances; horizontal scaling increases instance size","Vertical scaling increases the size of an existing instance; horizontal scaling adds more instances","They are the same thing","Vertical scaling is for databases; horizontal scaling is for web servers only"],"correct_answer":"Vertical scaling increases the size of an existing instance; horizontal scaling adds more instances","explanation":"Vertical scaling (scale up) means upgrading to a larger instance type. Horizontal scaling (scale out) means adding more instances. AWS generally recommends horizontal scaling for resilience.","memory_technique":"Vertical = Up (bigger machine). Horizontal = Out (more machines). Skyscraper vs. suburb.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Vertical scaling is the traditional IT approach — buy a bigger server. Horizontal scaling is the cloud-native approach — add more commodity servers."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Well-Architected Framework?","options":["A set of AWS pricing guidelines","A framework of best practices across five pillars for building cloud workloads","A compliance certification program","A tool for migrating on-premises workloads"],"correct_answer":"A framework of best practices across five pillars for building cloud workloads","explanation":"The AWS Well-Architected Framework provides best practices across five pillars: Operational Excellence, Security, Reliability, Performance Efficiency, and Cost Optimisation.","memory_technique":"OSRPC: Operations, Security, Reliability, Performance, Cost. 'Our Secure Reliable Performance Costs.'","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"The Well-Architected Framework is AWS's equivalent of ITIL or ISO 27001 — a structured set of best practices for designing and operating cloud workloads."},
  {"question_text":"What is an Availability Zone (AZ)?","options":["A single data center","One or more discrete data centers with redundant power, networking, and connectivity","A geographic region","A CDN edge location"],"correct_answer":"One or more discrete data centers with redundant power, networking, and connectivity","explanation":"An AZ consists of one or more discrete data centers with redundant power, networking, and connectivity. AZs within a Region are interconnected with high-bandwidth, low-latency networking.","memory_technique":"AZ = Armored Zone. Each AZ is physically separate but connected — like separate buildings on a campus with underground fiber.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"AZs are equivalent to separate data center buildings with independent power feeds and network paths — the same redundancy pattern used in enterprise data center design."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of deploying an application across multiple Availability Zones?","options":["To reduce costs","To improve fault tolerance and high availability","To increase network latency","To comply with data residency requirements"],"correct_answer":"To improve fault tolerance and high availability","explanation":"Deploying across multiple AZs means if one AZ experiences an outage, your application continues running in the other AZs. This is the foundation of high availability on AWS.","memory_technique":"Multi-AZ = Multiple safety nets. If one net breaks, the others catch you.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Multi-AZ deployment mirrors traditional active-active data center configurations where workloads run simultaneously in two locations for redundancy."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Cloud Adoption Framework (CAF)?","options":["A pricing model for cloud services","A framework that helps organisations develop a plan for cloud adoption","A security compliance standard","A tool for monitoring cloud costs"],"correct_answer":"A framework that helps organisations develop a plan for cloud adoption","explanation":"The AWS CAF provides guidance and best practices to help organisations develop an efficient and effective plan for their cloud adoption journey across six perspectives: Business, People, Governance, Platform, Security, and Operations.","memory_technique":"CAF = Cloud Adoption Framework. Six perspectives = six lenses to view your cloud journey through.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"The CAF is similar to TOGAF (The Open Group Architecture Framework) — a structured approach to planning and executing a major IT transformation."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between a public cloud and a private cloud?","options":["Public cloud is free; private cloud is paid","Public cloud resources are shared among multiple customers; private cloud is dedicated to one organisation","Public cloud is less secure; private cloud is more secure","Public cloud is on-premises; private cloud is hosted by a provider"],"correct_answer":"Public cloud resources are shared among multiple customers; private cloud is dedicated to one organisation","explanation":"In a public cloud, resources are owned and operated by a third-party provider and shared among multiple customers (multi-tenant). A private cloud is dedicated infrastructure for a single organisation.","memory_technique":"Public = shared apartment building. Private = your own house. Both can be equally secure with the right locks.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Public cloud is multi-tenant hosting; private cloud is equivalent to a dedicated colocation environment or on-premises data center."},
  {"question_text":"What is a hybrid cloud?","options":["A cloud that uses both Linux and Windows servers","A combination of public cloud and private cloud or on-premises infrastructure","A cloud that spans multiple public cloud providers","A cloud with both free and paid tiers"],"correct_answer":"A combination of public cloud and private cloud or on-premises infrastructure","explanation":"A hybrid cloud combines public cloud services with private cloud or on-premises infrastructure, connected by technology that allows data and applications to be shared between them.","memory_technique":"Hybrid = best of both worlds. Keep sensitive data on-premises, use public cloud for scalable workloads.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Most enterprises use hybrid cloud — keeping regulated workloads on-premises while using public cloud for development, testing, or burst capacity."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Outposts?","options":["A service for connecting to AWS via dedicated network links","AWS-managed infrastructure delivered to your on-premises location","A tool for migrating databases to AWS","A service for running containers on AWS"],"correct_answer":"AWS-managed infrastructure delivered to your on-premises location","explanation":"AWS Outposts brings AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to your on-premises location. It allows you to run AWS services locally while connecting to the AWS Region.","memory_technique":"Outposts = AWS outpost in your building. AWS sends a rack of servers to your data center.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Outposts is like having a branch office of AWS in your data center — you get the same AWS APIs and services but running on your premises for latency or data residency requirements."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Personal Health Dashboard?","options":["A dashboard showing your AWS account costs","A personalised view of AWS service health events that affect your resources","A tool for monitoring EC2 instance performance","A security compliance dashboard"],"correct_answer":"A personalised view of AWS service health events that affect your resources","explanation":"The AWS Personal Health Dashboard provides alerts and remediation guidance when AWS is experiencing events that may impact your specific resources, unlike the general Service Health Dashboard.","memory_technique":"Personal Health Dashboard = your doctor's report, not the hospital's general status board. Personalised to YOUR resources.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"The Personal Health Dashboard is equivalent to a personalised monitoring alert system — it filters AWS-wide events to show only those affecting your specific account and resources."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Service Health Dashboard?","options":["A personalised view of events affecting your resources","A public dashboard showing the current status of all AWS services globally","A tool for monitoring your application performance","A billing and cost dashboard"],"correct_answer":"A public dashboard showing the current status of all AWS services globally","explanation":"The AWS Service Health Dashboard (status.aws.amazon.com) shows the current status of all AWS services across all regions. It is publicly accessible and shows historical incidents.","memory_technique":"Service Health Dashboard = AWS's public status page. Like checking if your internet provider is down — it's public information.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"The Service Health Dashboard is equivalent to a public status page like status.github.com or status.salesforce.com — showing whether the service is operational."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Migration Acceleration Program (MAP)?","options":["A tool for automatically migrating databases","A program providing financial support, training, and services to help customers migrate to AWS","A service for migrating virtual machines","A compliance framework for cloud migration"],"correct_answer":"A program providing financial support, training, and services to help customers migrate to AWS","explanation":"The AWS Migration Acceleration Program (MAP) provides financial support, training, and professional services to help customers accelerate their migration to AWS.","memory_technique":"MAP = Migration Assistance Program. AWS gives you a map (and money) to help you find your way to the cloud.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"MAP is similar to vendor migration incentive programs — like Microsoft's FastTrack or Google's migration credits — where the cloud provider subsidises the cost of moving to their platform."},
]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SECURITY AND COMPLIANCE — Difficulty 2
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
questions += [
  {"question_text":"What is an IAM Role?","options":["A permanent set of credentials for a user","An identity with permissions that can be assumed by users, services, or applications temporarily","A group of IAM users","A type of IAM policy"],"correct_answer":"An identity with permissions that can be assumed by users, services, or applications temporarily","explanation":"An IAM Role is an identity with permission policies that can be assumed by trusted entities. Unlike users, roles do not have long-term credentials — they provide temporary security credentials.","memory_technique":"Role = Temporary costume. The entity 'wears' the role's permissions temporarily. No keys stored = no keys stolen.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"IAM Roles are equivalent to service accounts in Active Directory — a non-human identity used by applications/services to access resources without embedding user credentials."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between an IAM User and an IAM Role?","options":["Users are for humans; roles are for services only","Users have permanent credentials; roles provide temporary credentials that can be assumed","Users can only read; roles can write","There is no difference"],"correct_answer":"Users have permanent credentials; roles provide temporary credentials that can be assumed","explanation":"IAM Users have long-term credentials (passwords, access keys). IAM Roles provide temporary credentials via STS (Security Token Service) and can be assumed by users, services, or applications.","memory_technique":"User = permanent ID badge. Role = visitor badge that expires. Roles are safer for services.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Users are like employee accounts; roles are like contractor access cards that expire. Best practice is to use roles for applications and services rather than embedding user credentials."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS KMS used for?","options":["Managing SSH keys for EC2 instances","Creating and managing cryptographic keys used to encrypt data","Storing application passwords","Managing SSL/TLS certificates"],"correct_answer":"Creating and managing cryptographic keys used to encrypt data","explanation":"AWS KMS is a managed service for creating and controlling the cryptographic keys used to encrypt your data. It integrates with most AWS services to encrypt data at rest.","memory_technique":"KMS = Key Master Service. It's the locksmith that creates and manages the keys to your encrypted data vaults.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"KMS replaces on-premises Hardware Security Modules (HSMs) and key management software like Thales or SafeNet that enterprises use to manage encryption keys."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon GuardDuty?","options":["A web application firewall","A threat detection service that analyses logs for malicious activity","A compliance reporting tool","A network traffic analyser"],"correct_answer":"A threat detection service that analyses logs for malicious activity","explanation":"Amazon GuardDuty is a threat detection service that continuously monitors for malicious activity by analysing CloudTrail logs, VPC Flow Logs, and DNS logs using machine learning.","memory_technique":"GuardDuty = Guard on Duty 24/7. It's your always-on security guard watching for suspicious activity.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"GuardDuty replaces traditional IDS/IPS systems and SIEM correlation rules. It's like having a 24/7 SOC analyst automatically analysing your logs for threats."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Config?","options":["A service for managing application configuration files","A service that continuously monitors and records AWS resource configurations","A tool for configuring EC2 instances","A network configuration service"],"correct_answer":"A service that continuously monitors and records AWS resource configurations","explanation":"AWS Config continuously monitors and records your AWS resource configurations and allows you to evaluate them against desired configurations using Config Rules.","memory_technique":"Config = Configuration Police. It watches for rule violations and keeps a history of every configuration change.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"AWS Config is equivalent to configuration management databases (CMDB) combined with compliance scanning tools — it tracks what your infrastructure looks like and whether it meets your standards."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon Inspector?","options":["A service for inspecting S3 bucket contents","An automated security assessment service for EC2 instances and container images","A network traffic inspection tool","A compliance audit service"],"correct_answer":"An automated security assessment service for EC2 instances and container images","explanation":"Amazon Inspector automatically assesses EC2 instances and container images for software vulnerabilities and unintended network exposure, providing a risk score and remediation guidance.","memory_technique":"Inspector = Security Inspector. It inspects your EC2 instances for vulnerabilities, like a building inspector checking for code violations.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Amazon Inspector replaces vulnerability scanning tools like Nessus or Qualys. It automatically scans for known CVEs and network exposure without manual scheduling."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of Security Groups in AWS?","options":["To group IAM users with similar permissions","To act as virtual firewalls controlling inbound and outbound traffic for EC2 instances","To encrypt data at rest","To monitor network traffic"],"correct_answer":"To act as virtual firewalls controlling inbound and outbound traffic for EC2 instances","explanation":"Security Groups act as virtual firewalls for EC2 instances. They control inbound and outbound traffic at the instance level using allow rules (there are no deny rules in Security Groups).","memory_technique":"Security Group = Bouncer for your EC2 instance. Only lets in traffic you explicitly allow.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Security Groups are equivalent to host-based firewall rules (Windows Firewall, iptables) — they control which traffic can reach a specific server."},
  {"question_text":"What is a Network Access Control List (NACL)?","options":["A list of approved IAM users","A stateless firewall that controls traffic at the subnet level","A list of allowed IP addresses for S3 buckets","A DNS access control mechanism"],"correct_answer":"A stateless firewall that controls traffic at the subnet level","explanation":"NACLs are stateless firewalls that control inbound and outbound traffic at the subnet level. Unlike Security Groups, NACLs support both allow and deny rules and are stateless.","memory_technique":"NACL = Network ACL = subnet-level firewall. Stateless = you must explicitly allow both directions of traffic.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"NACLs are equivalent to traditional network ACLs on routers and switches — they filter traffic at the network boundary rather than at the individual host level."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Secrets Manager?","options":["A service for managing IAM user passwords","A service for securely storing, rotating, and retrieving secrets like database credentials and API keys","A password manager for AWS console access","A service for encrypting S3 objects"],"correct_answer":"A service for securely storing, rotating, and retrieving secrets like database credentials and API keys","explanation":"AWS Secrets Manager helps you protect access to your applications, services, and IT resources by enabling you to rotate, manage, and retrieve database credentials, API keys, and other secrets.","memory_technique":"Secrets Manager = Secret vault with automatic key rotation. Stores secrets and rotates them automatically so you don't have to.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Secrets Manager replaces storing credentials in config files or environment variables. It's equivalent to enterprise secret management tools like HashiCorp Vault or CyberArk."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Certificate Manager (ACM)?","options":["A service for managing IAM certificates","A service for provisioning, managing, and deploying SSL/TLS certificates","A compliance certification tracking tool","A service for managing code signing certificates"],"correct_answer":"A service for provisioning, managing, and deploying SSL/TLS certificates","explanation":"AWS Certificate Manager handles the complexity of creating, storing, and renewing SSL/TLS certificates. It integrates with CloudFront, ELB, and API Gateway for automatic certificate deployment.","memory_technique":"ACM = Automatic Certificate Manager. Free SSL certs that renew themselves — no more certificate expiry alerts at 2am.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"ACM replaces the manual process of purchasing SSL certificates from CAs like DigiCert or Comodo, generating CSRs, and manually installing and renewing certificates."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon Macie?","options":["A threat detection service","A service that uses machine learning to discover and protect sensitive data in S3","A web application firewall","A network monitoring service"],"correct_answer":"A service that uses machine learning to discover and protect sensitive data in S3","explanation":"Amazon Macie uses machine learning to automatically discover, classify, and protect sensitive data in S3. It identifies PII, financial data, and other sensitive information.","memory_technique":"Macie = Data Detective. Like a detective that finds hidden sensitive data in your S3 buckets.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Macie replaces traditional DLP (Data Loss Prevention) tools like Symantec DLP or Forcepoint that scan file servers and databases for sensitive data patterns."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of VPC Flow Logs?","options":["To log application errors","To capture information about IP traffic going to and from network interfaces in a VPC","To monitor EC2 instance performance","To log S3 access requests"],"correct_answer":"To capture information about IP traffic going to and from network interfaces in a VPC","explanation":"VPC Flow Logs capture information about the IP traffic going to and from network interfaces in your VPC. They can be used for security analysis, troubleshooting, and compliance.","memory_technique":"Flow Logs = traffic camera for your VPC. Records every car (packet) that passes through.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"VPC Flow Logs are equivalent to NetFlow or sFlow data from network switches and routers — they provide visibility into network traffic patterns for security and troubleshooting."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Organizations?","options":["A tool for organising EC2 instances into groups","A service for managing multiple AWS accounts centrally","A project management tool for AWS teams","A service for organising S3 buckets"],"correct_answer":"A service for managing multiple AWS accounts centrally","explanation":"AWS Organizations allows you to centrally manage multiple AWS accounts. It provides consolidated billing, account management, and the ability to apply Service Control Policies (SCPs) across accounts.","memory_technique":"Organizations = Corporate HQ for your AWS accounts. One place to manage all your accounts, billing, and policies.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"AWS Organizations is equivalent to Active Directory domains and forests — a hierarchical structure for managing multiple organisational units with centralised policy control."},
]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# TECHNOLOGY — Difficulty 2
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
questions += [
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between Amazon S3 and Amazon EBS?","options":["S3 is block storage; EBS is object storage","S3 is object storage accessible via HTTP; EBS is block storage attached to EC2 instances","S3 is for databases; EBS is for static websites","They are the same service"],"correct_answer":"S3 is object storage accessible via HTTP; EBS is block storage attached to EC2 instances","explanation":"S3 stores objects accessible via HTTP/HTTPS APIs — ideal for unstructured data, backups, and static content. EBS provides block-level storage volumes that attach to EC2 instances like a virtual hard drive.","memory_technique":"S3 = Shelf storage (accessible from anywhere). EBS = External hard drive (plugged into one EC2 at a time).","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"S3 is like a NAS accessible over the internet. EBS is like a SAN LUN attached directly to a server."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon EFS?","options":["A block storage service","A managed elastic file system that can be mounted by multiple EC2 instances simultaneously","An object storage service","A database service"],"correct_answer":"A managed elastic file system that can be mounted by multiple EC2 instances simultaneously","explanation":"Amazon EFS (Elastic File System) provides a simple, scalable, elastic file system for Linux-based workloads. Multiple EC2 instances can mount the same EFS file system simultaneously.","memory_technique":"EFS = Elastic File System. Like a shared network drive that multiple servers can access at the same time.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"EFS is equivalent to NFS (Network File System) shares in traditional IT — a shared file system that multiple servers can mount and access concurrently."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon ElastiCache?","options":["A managed relational database","A managed in-memory caching service supporting Redis and Memcached","A content delivery network","A message queue service"],"correct_answer":"A managed in-memory caching service supporting Redis and Memcached","explanation":"Amazon ElastiCache is a fully managed in-memory caching service that supports Redis and Memcached. It improves application performance by caching frequently accessed data.","memory_technique":"ElastiCache = Elastic Cache. Stretchy memory cache that scales with your app. Redis/Memcached without the ops headache.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"ElastiCache replaces self-managed Redis or Memcached clusters. Instead of managing replication, failover, and patching, AWS handles it."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon Redshift?","options":["A managed NoSQL database","A fully managed data warehouse for analytics","A real-time streaming service","A managed MySQL database"],"correct_answer":"A fully managed data warehouse for analytics","explanation":"Amazon Redshift is a fully managed, petabyte-scale data warehouse. It uses columnar storage and massively parallel processing (MPP) to deliver fast query performance on large datasets.","memory_technique":"Redshift = Red-hot analytics. Columnar storage = reading only the columns you need for fast queries.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Redshift replaces on-premises data warehouse appliances like Teradata, Netezza, or Oracle Exadata. It provides MPP analytics without managing hardware."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Direct Connect?","options":["A VPN service over the internet","A dedicated private network connection from your on-premises data center to AWS","A service for connecting VPCs together","A DNS routing service"],"correct_answer":"A dedicated private network connection from your on-premises data center to AWS","explanation":"AWS Direct Connect provides a dedicated private network connection from your on-premises data center to AWS, bypassing the public internet for more consistent performance and lower latency.","memory_technique":"Direct Connect = Direct line to AWS. Like a private leased line vs. the public internet — dedicated bandwidth, no internet congestion.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Direct Connect is equivalent to an MPLS private WAN circuit or a leased line to a colocation facility — dedicated connectivity that enterprises use for branch office connections."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Auto Scaling?","options":["A service that automatically backs up EC2 instances","A service that automatically adjusts the number of EC2 instances based on demand","A service that automatically patches EC2 instances","A service that automatically distributes traffic"],"correct_answer":"A service that automatically adjusts the number of EC2 instances based on demand","explanation":"AWS Auto Scaling monitors your applications and automatically adjusts capacity to maintain steady, predictable performance at the lowest possible cost.","memory_technique":"Auto Scaling = Automatic thermostat for compute. Too hot (high load)? Add instances. Too cold (low load)? Remove them.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Auto Scaling replaces manual capacity management. Traditional IT required pre-provisioning for peak load; Auto Scaling dynamically adjusts like a staffing agency that adds/removes workers based on workload."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon Aurora?","options":["A NoSQL database","A MySQL and PostgreSQL-compatible relational database built for the cloud with up to 5x better performance","A data warehouse service","An in-memory database"],"correct_answer":"A MySQL and PostgreSQL-compatible relational database built for the cloud with up to 5x better performance","explanation":"Amazon Aurora is a MySQL and PostgreSQL-compatible relational database built for the cloud. It delivers up to 5x the throughput of MySQL and 3x the throughput of PostgreSQL.","memory_technique":"Aurora = Aurora Borealis — brilliant and fast. MySQL/PostgreSQL compatible but much faster and more resilient.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Aurora is a drop-in replacement for MySQL or PostgreSQL that provides cloud-native performance improvements — like upgrading from a standard car engine to a turbocharged one."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS CloudFormation?","options":["A monitoring service","Infrastructure as code service using JSON or YAML templates to provision AWS resources","A deployment pipeline service","A configuration management service"],"correct_answer":"Infrastructure as code service using JSON or YAML templates to provision AWS resources","explanation":"AWS CloudFormation allows you to model and provision AWS resources using JSON or YAML templates. It treats infrastructure as code, enabling version control and repeatable deployments.","memory_technique":"CloudFormation = Cloud Blueprint. Define your infrastructure in code and CloudFormation builds it.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"CloudFormation is equivalent to Terraform or Ansible for infrastructure provisioning. It replaces manual console clicks with repeatable, version-controlled infrastructure definitions."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon Kinesis?","options":["A message queue service","A platform for collecting, processing, and analysing real-time streaming data","A batch processing service","A data warehouse service"],"correct_answer":"A platform for collecting, processing, and analysing real-time streaming data","explanation":"Amazon Kinesis makes it easy to collect, process, and analyse real-time streaming data. It includes Kinesis Data Streams, Kinesis Data Firehose, and Kinesis Data Analytics.","memory_technique":"Kinesis = Kinetic energy (always moving data). Real-time streams of data flowing continuously.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Kinesis replaces traditional ETL batch processing with real-time streaming. It's equivalent to Apache Kafka for event streaming but fully managed by AWS."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Glue?","options":["A service for connecting VPCs","A fully managed ETL service for data integration and preparation","A database migration service","A data visualisation service"],"correct_answer":"A fully managed ETL service for data integration and preparation","explanation":"AWS Glue is a fully managed ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) service that makes it easy to prepare and load data for analytics. It includes a data catalog and serverless Spark environment.","memory_technique":"Glue = Sticks data together. Extracts from sources, transforms it, loads it to destinations.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"AWS Glue replaces traditional ETL tools like Informatica, Talend, or SSIS. It provides the same data transformation capabilities in a serverless, managed environment."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon Athena?","options":["A managed data warehouse","An interactive query service that analyses data in S3 using standard SQL","A real-time streaming service","A NoSQL database"],"correct_answer":"An interactive query service that analyses data in S3 using standard SQL","explanation":"Amazon Athena is an interactive query service that makes it easy to analyse data in Amazon S3 using standard SQL. It is serverless — no infrastructure to manage and you pay per query.","memory_technique":"Athena = Goddess of wisdom. Athena is wise enough to query your S3 data directly with SQL — no loading required.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Athena is equivalent to running SQL queries directly against files on a NAS — no need to load data into a database first. It's like having a SQL engine that reads CSV/Parquet files directly."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Fargate?","options":["A container registry service","A serverless compute engine for containers that removes the need to manage EC2 instances","A managed Kubernetes service","A virtual machine service"],"correct_answer":"A serverless compute engine for containers that removes the need to manage EC2 instances","explanation":"AWS Fargate is a serverless compute engine for containers. It works with ECS and EKS, removing the need to provision and manage EC2 instances for container workloads.","memory_technique":"Fargate = Far from managing gates (servers). Serverless containers — you just define what to run, not where.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Fargate is equivalent to a managed Kubernetes node pool or a PaaS container platform. You get container orchestration without managing the underlying VM fleet."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon ECS?","options":["A managed Kubernetes service","A fully managed container orchestration service","A serverless function service","A virtual machine service"],"correct_answer":"A fully managed container orchestration service","explanation":"Amazon ECS (Elastic Container Service) is a fully managed container orchestration service that makes it easy to deploy, manage, and scale containerised applications.","memory_technique":"ECS = Elastic Container Service. Like a conductor for your container orchestra — manages where and how containers run.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"ECS is equivalent to Docker Swarm or a simplified Kubernetes — it orchestrates containers across a cluster of EC2 instances or Fargate."},
]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# BILLING AND PRICING — Difficulty 2
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
questions += [
  {"question_text":"Which EC2 pricing option provides the largest discount but can be interrupted by AWS?","options":["Reserved Instances","On-Demand Instances","Spot Instances","Dedicated Hosts"],"correct_answer":"Spot Instances","explanation":"Spot Instances use spare EC2 capacity and can offer discounts of up to 90% compared to On-Demand prices. AWS can reclaim Spot Instances with a 2-minute warning when capacity is needed.","memory_technique":"Spot = Spot price at an auction. Cheap when supply is high, but the auctioneer can take it back.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Spot Instances are like buying standby airline tickets — huge discount, but you might get bumped. Ideal for batch processing or CI/CD pipelines that can restart."},
  {"question_text":"What is a Dedicated Host?","options":["An EC2 instance with dedicated CPU","A physical server fully dedicated to your use","A Reserved Instance with dedicated networking","An instance with dedicated storage"],"correct_answer":"A physical server fully dedicated to your use","explanation":"A Dedicated Host is a physical EC2 server dedicated for your use. It allows you to use your existing server-bound software licences and helps meet compliance requirements.","memory_technique":"Dedicated Host = Your own physical server in AWS. No sharing with other customers — the whole machine is yours.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Dedicated Hosts are equivalent to owning a physical server in a colocation facility — you have the entire machine to yourself, which is required for some software licences (Oracle, Windows Server)."},
  {"question_text":"What is a Dedicated Instance?","options":["An EC2 instance that runs on hardware dedicated to a single customer but may share the host with other instances from the same account","A physical server dedicated to one customer","An instance with dedicated network bandwidth","A Reserved Instance with dedicated storage"],"correct_answer":"An EC2 instance that runs on hardware dedicated to a single customer but may share the host with other instances from the same account","explanation":"Dedicated Instances run on hardware dedicated to a single customer. Unlike Dedicated Hosts, you don't have visibility into the physical host and instances from the same account may share the host.","memory_technique":"Dedicated Instance = dedicated hardware, but you don't control which physical server. Dedicated Host = you control the specific physical server.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Dedicated Instances are for compliance requirements that mandate single-tenant hardware but don't require specific host affinity for licence management."},
  {"question_text":"What does 'All Upfront' mean for Reserved Instances?","options":["You pay nothing upfront and are billed monthly","You pay the full Reserved Instance cost upfront for the maximum discount","You pay half upfront and half monthly","You pay upfront only for the first month"],"correct_answer":"You pay the full Reserved Instance cost upfront for the maximum discount","explanation":"All Upfront payment for Reserved Instances means you pay the entire cost at the start of the term. This provides the maximum discount compared to Partial Upfront or No Upfront options.","memory_technique":"All Upfront = Pay everything now, save the most. Like buying a car outright vs. financing — upfront costs more initially but saves money overall.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"All Upfront Reserved Instances are like prepaying for a 1 or 3-year server lease — maximum discount in exchange for full commitment."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Cost and Usage Report (CUR)?","options":["A monthly invoice from AWS","The most comprehensive set of AWS cost and usage data available, delivered to S3","A real-time cost monitoring dashboard","A tool for forecasting future costs"],"correct_answer":"The most comprehensive set of AWS cost and usage data available, delivered to S3","explanation":"The AWS Cost and Usage Report contains the most comprehensive set of cost and usage data. It is delivered to an S3 bucket and can be queried with Athena or loaded into a data warehouse.","memory_technique":"CUR = Comprehensive Usage Report. The raw data behind your AWS bill — every line item, every hour, every resource.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"The CUR is equivalent to a detailed billing extract from an ERP system — raw transactional data that finance teams use for chargeback and cost allocation analysis."},
  {"question_text":"What are Cost Allocation Tags?","options":["Labels applied to AWS resources to track costs by project, team, or environment","Tags that automatically reduce costs","Labels that identify security vulnerabilities","Tags used to organise EC2 instances"],"correct_answer":"Labels applied to AWS resources to track costs by project, team, or environment","explanation":"Cost Allocation Tags are key-value pairs applied to AWS resources. After activating them in Billing, they appear in Cost Explorer and the CUR, enabling cost breakdown by business unit or project.","memory_technique":"Tags = Price labels on resources. Tag every resource with its owner/project, then your bill automatically breaks down by department.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Cost allocation tags are equivalent to cost center codes in enterprise financial systems — they enable IT chargeback by attributing cloud costs to specific business units."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Marketplace?","options":["A store for purchasing physical AWS hardware","A digital catalogue of third-party software and services that run on AWS","A marketplace for buying Reserved Instances","A store for AWS training courses"],"correct_answer":"A digital catalogue of third-party software and services that run on AWS","explanation":"AWS Marketplace is a digital catalogue with thousands of software listings from independent software vendors. You can find, test, buy, and deploy software that runs on AWS.","memory_technique":"AWS Marketplace = App Store for AWS. Browse, buy, and deploy third-party software with one click.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"AWS Marketplace is equivalent to a software procurement portal — instead of negotiating contracts with vendors, you can subscribe to software directly and have it billed through your AWS account."},
  {"question_text":"What is the Reserved Instance Marketplace?","options":["A place to buy new Reserved Instances from AWS","A marketplace where customers can sell their unused Reserved Instances to other customers","A tool for comparing Reserved Instance prices","A marketplace for Spot Instances"],"correct_answer":"A marketplace where customers can sell their unused Reserved Instances to other customers","explanation":"The Reserved Instance Marketplace allows customers to sell their unused Standard Reserved Instances to other AWS customers. This provides flexibility if your capacity needs change.","memory_technique":"RI Marketplace = eBay for Reserved Instances. Sell your unused reservations to someone who needs them.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"The RI Marketplace is like a secondary market for prepaid server leases — if your business needs change, you can sell your remaining commitment rather than paying for unused capacity."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Compute Optimizer?","options":["A tool for optimising network performance","A service that recommends optimal AWS compute resources based on your usage patterns","A tool for optimising database queries","A service for optimising S3 storage costs"],"correct_answer":"A service that recommends optimal AWS compute resources based on your usage patterns","explanation":"AWS Compute Optimizer uses machine learning to analyse your resource utilisation and provide recommendations for optimal EC2 instance types, EBS volumes, Lambda functions, and ECS tasks.","memory_technique":"Compute Optimizer = Personal trainer for your compute. Analyses your usage and recommends the right size — not too big, not too small.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Compute Optimizer is equivalent to a capacity planning tool that analyses server utilisation and recommends right-sizing — replacing the manual process of reviewing CPU/memory metrics."},
  {"question_text":"What is S3 Intelligent-Tiering?","options":["A storage class that automatically moves objects between access tiers based on usage patterns","A tool for intelligently routing S3 requests","A feature that automatically encrypts S3 objects","A service for intelligently replicating S3 data"],"correct_answer":"A storage class that automatically moves objects between access tiers based on usage patterns","explanation":"S3 Intelligent-Tiering automatically moves objects between frequent and infrequent access tiers based on changing access patterns, optimising storage costs without performance impact.","memory_technique":"Intelligent-Tiering = Smart filing system. Frequently used files stay on your desk; rarely used files go to the archive automatically.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"S3 Intelligent-Tiering is equivalent to automated storage tiering in enterprise storage systems (like NetApp FabricPool) — hot data stays on fast storage, cold data moves to cheaper tiers automatically."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between AWS Cost Explorer and AWS Budgets?","options":["They are the same service","Cost Explorer analyses historical and forecasted costs; Budgets sets alerts for spending thresholds","Cost Explorer sets alerts; Budgets analyses costs","Cost Explorer is for billing; Budgets is for forecasting only"],"correct_answer":"Cost Explorer analyses historical and forecasted costs; Budgets sets alerts for spending thresholds","explanation":"Cost Explorer is for visualising and analysing your cost and usage data. AWS Budgets is for setting custom spending thresholds and receiving alerts when costs approach or exceed those thresholds.","memory_technique":"Explorer = explores your costs (analysis). Budgets = budget alarm (alerts). Explorer looks back and forward; Budgets rings the bell when you overspend.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":2,"it_context_mapping":"Cost Explorer is like a financial reporting tool; Budgets is like a spending alert system. Together they provide both visibility and control over cloud spending."},
]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# CLOUD CONCEPTS — Difficulty 3
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
questions += [
  {"question_text":"A company wants to ensure their application remains available even if an entire AWS Region fails. What architecture should they implement?","options":["Deploy across multiple Availability Zones in one Region","Deploy across multiple AWS Regions","Use a single large EC2 instance","Use Reserved Instances"],"correct_answer":"Deploy across multiple AWS Regions","explanation":"To survive a full Region failure, you must deploy across multiple Regions. Multi-AZ protects against AZ failures but not Region-wide outages. Multi-Region architecture provides the highest level of availability.","memory_technique":"AZ failure = city disaster. Region failure = country disaster. Multi-Region = international backup.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Multi-Region architecture mirrors traditional geographic DR — having a hot standby in a different city or country to survive regional disasters like power grid failures or natural disasters."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between RPO and RTO in disaster recovery?","options":["RPO is the maximum acceptable downtime; RTO is the maximum acceptable data loss","RPO is the maximum acceptable data loss; RTO is the maximum acceptable downtime","They are the same metric","RPO applies to databases; RTO applies to applications"],"correct_answer":"RPO is the maximum acceptable data loss; RTO is the maximum acceptable downtime","explanation":"RPO (Recovery Point Objective) is the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time. RTO (Recovery Time Objective) is the maximum acceptable time to restore service after a failure.","memory_technique":"RPO = how much data you can afford to lose (Point in time). RTO = how long you can afford to be down (Time to recover).","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"RPO and RTO are standard DR metrics used in business continuity planning. They drive decisions about backup frequency (RPO) and infrastructure redundancy (RTO)."},
  {"question_text":"Which disaster recovery strategy has the lowest RTO but highest cost?","options":["Backup and Restore","Pilot Light","Warm Standby","Multi-Site Active-Active"],"correct_answer":"Multi-Site Active-Active","explanation":"Multi-Site Active-Active runs full production workloads in multiple regions simultaneously. It has near-zero RTO because traffic is already flowing to both sites, but it is the most expensive option.","memory_technique":"Active-Active = Always on everywhere. Zero downtime, maximum cost. Like having two fully staffed offices.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Multi-Site Active-Active mirrors traditional active-active data center configurations where both sites handle live traffic simultaneously — the gold standard for mission-critical systems."},
  {"question_text":"What is the Pilot Light disaster recovery strategy?","options":["Running a full copy of production in a second region","Keeping only the core components running in a second region, ready to scale up","Taking regular backups to S3","Running a scaled-down version of production in a second region"],"correct_answer":"Keeping only the core components running in a second region, ready to scale up","explanation":"Pilot Light keeps only the critical core components (like a database) running in the DR region. When disaster strikes, you scale up the remaining components around the running core.","memory_technique":"Pilot Light = just the pilot flame burning. The core is lit; you turn up the heat (scale up) when needed.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Pilot Light is like keeping a generator on standby with fuel — the core infrastructure is ready but not fully running, reducing costs while enabling faster recovery than cold backup."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Acceptable Use Policy (AUP)?","options":["A policy defining how AWS charges for services","A policy describing prohibited uses of AWS services","A policy for acceptable response times","A policy for acceptable data storage limits"],"correct_answer":"A policy describing prohibited uses of AWS services","explanation":"The AWS Acceptable Use Policy describes prohibited uses of AWS services, including illegal activities, sending unsolicited emails, and activities that violate others' rights.","memory_technique":"AUP = Acceptable Use Policy. The rules of the road for using AWS — what you're NOT allowed to do.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"The AUP is equivalent to an ISP's acceptable use policy or a corporate IT acceptable use policy — it defines the boundaries of permitted use."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Partner Network (APN)?","options":["A network of AWS data centers","A global community of AWS partners who build solutions and services on AWS","A private network for AWS employees","A network of AWS Marketplace vendors only"],"correct_answer":"A global community of AWS partners who build solutions and services on AWS","explanation":"The AWS Partner Network (APN) is a global community of technology and consulting businesses that build solutions and services on AWS. Partners include ISVs, MSPs, and consulting firms.","memory_technique":"APN = AWS's partner ecosystem. Like a franchise network — partners are certified to sell and implement AWS solutions.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"The APN is equivalent to Microsoft's partner network or Cisco's channel partner program — a tiered ecosystem of resellers, integrators, and ISVs certified to deliver solutions on the platform."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between the AWS Service Health Dashboard and the AWS Personal Health Dashboard?","options":["They are the same dashboard","The Service Health Dashboard shows global AWS status; the Personal Health Dashboard shows events affecting your specific resources","The Service Health Dashboard is for billing; the Personal Health Dashboard is for security","The Service Health Dashboard requires a paid support plan"],"correct_answer":"The Service Health Dashboard shows global AWS status; the Personal Health Dashboard shows events affecting your specific resources","explanation":"The Service Health Dashboard shows the general status of all AWS services globally. The Personal Health Dashboard provides personalised alerts about events that specifically affect your AWS resources.","memory_technique":"Service Health = hospital's public status board. Personal Health = your own doctor's report. One is general; one is specific to you.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"The distinction mirrors the difference between a public status page (is the service up?) and a personalised monitoring alert (is YOUR service affected?)."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Well-Architected Tool?","options":["A tool for automatically fixing architectural issues","A free tool that helps review workloads against AWS best practices and identify improvement areas","A tool for deploying well-architected applications","A compliance scanning tool"],"correct_answer":"A free tool that helps review workloads against AWS best practices and identify improvement areas","explanation":"The AWS Well-Architected Tool provides a consistent process for reviewing and measuring your architecture against AWS best practices. It generates a report with identified risks and improvement recommendations.","memory_technique":"Well-Architected Tool = Architecture report card. Grades your workload against best practices and tells you where to improve.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"The Well-Architected Tool is equivalent to an IT architecture review board assessment — a structured evaluation of your design against established best practices."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Trusted Advisor 'Service Limits' check?","options":["A check that verifies your service agreements","A check that alerts you when you are approaching AWS service quotas","A check that verifies your IAM policies","A check that monitors your billing limits"],"correct_answer":"A check that alerts you when you are approaching AWS service quotas","explanation":"The Trusted Advisor Service Limits check monitors your usage against AWS service quotas (formerly called limits) and alerts you when you are approaching the maximum allowed values.","memory_technique":"Service Limits check = fuel gauge for AWS quotas. Warns you before you run out of capacity.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Service quota monitoring is equivalent to capacity management in traditional IT — tracking how close you are to hitting infrastructure limits before they cause outages."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of AWS Control Tower?","options":["A tool for monitoring network traffic","A service that automates the setup of a multi-account AWS environment with best practices","A container orchestration service","A tool for managing EC2 instances"],"correct_answer":"A service that automates the setup of a multi-account AWS environment with best practices","explanation":"AWS Control Tower automates the setup of a multi-account AWS environment (landing zone) based on AWS best practices. It provides account vending, centralised logging, and guardrails.","memory_technique":"Control Tower = Air Traffic Control for AWS accounts. Manages the landing zone and enforces flight rules (guardrails).","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Control Tower replaces custom account provisioning scripts. It's equivalent to an automated IT onboarding system that provisions new business units with pre-configured, compliant environments."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between AWS CloudTrail and Amazon CloudWatch?","options":["They are the same service","CloudTrail records API calls for auditing; CloudWatch monitors performance metrics and logs","CloudTrail monitors performance; CloudWatch records API calls","CloudTrail is for billing; CloudWatch is for security"],"correct_answer":"CloudTrail records API calls for auditing; CloudWatch monitors performance metrics and logs","explanation":"CloudTrail records who did what in your AWS account (API calls, user activity). CloudWatch monitors the performance and health of your AWS resources (CPU, memory, custom metrics, logs).","memory_technique":"CloudTrail = Who did what (audit log). CloudWatch = How is it performing (monitoring). Trail = history; Watch = real-time monitoring.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"CloudTrail is like a SIEM audit log; CloudWatch is like a monitoring platform (Nagios, Zabbix, Datadog). One tracks actions; the other tracks performance."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Shared Responsibility Model for a managed service like Amazon RDS?","options":["AWS manages everything including the data","The customer manages everything including the OS","AWS manages the infrastructure, OS, and database engine; the customer manages data, access control, and network configuration","The customer manages the OS; AWS manages the data"],"correct_answer":"AWS manages the infrastructure, OS, and database engine; the customer manages data, access control, and network configuration","explanation":"For managed services like RDS, AWS takes on more responsibility — managing the physical infrastructure, OS patching, and database engine. Customers are responsible for their data, IAM access, and network security groups.","memory_technique":"Managed service = AWS manages more. RDS: AWS patches the OS and DB engine; you manage your data and who can access it.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"This is equivalent to using a managed database hosting service — the provider manages the server and database software; you manage your data and application configuration."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Snow Family?","options":["A family of cold storage services","A family of physical devices for migrating large amounts of data to and from AWS","A family of serverless services","A family of database services"],"correct_answer":"A family of physical devices for migrating large amounts of data to and from AWS","explanation":"The AWS Snow Family includes Snowcone, Snowball Edge, and Snowmobile — physical devices for collecting and processing data at the edge and migrating large datasets to AWS when network transfer is impractical.","memory_technique":"Snow Family = Sneakernet at scale. When the internet is too slow, ship a truck full of hard drives. Snowcone (small) → Snowball (medium) → Snowmobile (massive truck).","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Snow devices are the modern equivalent of shipping backup tapes to an offsite facility. For large data migrations, physical transport beats network transfer — a principle true since the mainframe era."},
]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SECURITY AND COMPLIANCE — Difficulty 3
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
questions += [
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between AWS WAF and AWS Shield?","options":["WAF protects against DDoS; Shield protects against SQL injection","WAF filters malicious web traffic at layer 7; Shield protects against DDoS attacks at layers 3 and 4","They are the same service","WAF is for EC2; Shield is for S3"],"correct_answer":"WAF filters malicious web traffic at layer 7; Shield protects against DDoS attacks at layers 3 and 4","explanation":"AWS WAF operates at layer 7 and filters HTTP/HTTPS traffic based on rules (SQL injection, XSS). AWS Shield operates at layers 3/4 and protects against volumetric DDoS attacks.","memory_technique":"WAF = Web Application Filter (layer 7 smart filtering). Shield = Brute force blocker (layer 3/4 volume attacks). WAF is the bouncer checking IDs; Shield is the crowd barrier.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"WAF is equivalent to a traditional WAF appliance (F5 ASM, Imperva). Shield is equivalent to upstream DDoS scrubbing services from ISPs or CDN providers."},
  {"question_text":"Which IAM entity should be used to grant an EC2 instance permissions to access S3 without storing credentials on the instance?","options":["IAM User with access keys","IAM Group","IAM Role","IAM Policy"],"correct_answer":"IAM Role","explanation":"IAM Roles should be used to grant AWS services permissions to access other AWS services. An EC2 instance assumes a role, which provides temporary credentials automatically — no need to store long-term access keys.","memory_technique":"Role = Temporary costume. The EC2 instance 'wears' the role's permissions temporarily. No keys stored = no keys stolen.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"IAM Roles for EC2 are equivalent to service accounts in Active Directory — a non-human identity used by applications to access resources without embedding user credentials."},
  {"question_text":"What is a Service Control Policy (SCP) in AWS Organizations?","options":["A policy that controls which services are available in the AWS Marketplace","A policy that defines the maximum permissions for accounts in an AWS Organization","A policy that controls network traffic between services","A billing policy for AWS accounts"],"correct_answer":"A policy that defines the maximum permissions for accounts in an AWS Organization","explanation":"SCPs define the maximum permissions for accounts in an AWS Organization. They act as guardrails — even if an IAM policy grants a permission, an SCP can deny it at the organisation level.","memory_technique":"SCP = Supreme Court Policy. Even account admins can't override it — it's the highest law in the AWS Organization.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"SCPs are equivalent to Group Policy Objects (GPOs) in Active Directory at the domain level — they set boundaries that override local administrator settings across all managed accounts."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of AWS Security Hub?","options":["A hub for managing EC2 security groups","A centralised security dashboard that aggregates findings from multiple AWS security services","A service for managing SSL certificates","A network security monitoring service"],"correct_answer":"A centralised security dashboard that aggregates findings from multiple AWS security services","explanation":"AWS Security Hub provides a comprehensive view of security alerts and compliance status across AWS accounts. It aggregates findings from GuardDuty, Inspector, Macie, and third-party tools.","memory_technique":"Security Hub = Central Security Command. All your security findings in one dashboard, like a unified SOC console.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Security Hub replaces traditional GRC tools and SIEM dashboards used to track compliance posture across infrastructure."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between Security Groups and Network ACLs?","options":["Security Groups are stateful and operate at the instance level; NACLs are stateless and operate at the subnet level","Security Groups are stateless; NACLs are stateful","Security Groups operate at the subnet level; NACLs operate at the instance level","They are the same thing"],"correct_answer":"Security Groups are stateful and operate at the instance level; NACLs are stateless and operate at the subnet level","explanation":"Security Groups are stateful (return traffic is automatically allowed) and apply to individual instances. NACLs are stateless (you must explicitly allow both directions) and apply to entire subnets.","memory_technique":"SG = Stateful Guard (instance level). NACL = Network ACL (subnet level, stateless). SG remembers; NACL forgets.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Security Groups are like host-based firewalls (Windows Firewall); NACLs are like network ACLs on routers. Both provide defence in depth."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS IAM Identity Center (formerly AWS SSO)?","options":["A service for managing IAM users","A service that provides single sign-on access to multiple AWS accounts and business applications","A multi-factor authentication service","A service for managing API keys"],"correct_answer":"A service that provides single sign-on access to multiple AWS accounts and business applications","explanation":"AWS IAM Identity Center provides SSO access to multiple AWS accounts and cloud applications. It integrates with identity providers like Active Directory and supports SAML 2.0.","memory_technique":"IAM Identity Center = Corporate ID badge for AWS. One login gets you into all your AWS accounts and apps.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"IAM Identity Center is equivalent to ADFS (Active Directory Federation Services) or Okta — a centralised identity provider that enables SSO across multiple applications and accounts."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of AWS CloudHSM?","options":["A managed key management service","A dedicated hardware security module in the AWS cloud for generating and managing cryptographic keys","A service for managing SSL certificates","A network encryption service"],"correct_answer":"A dedicated hardware security module in the AWS cloud for generating and managing cryptographic keys","explanation":"AWS CloudHSM provides dedicated hardware security modules (HSMs) in the AWS cloud. Unlike KMS, CloudHSM gives you exclusive control of the HSM — AWS cannot access your keys.","memory_technique":"CloudHSM = Cloud Hardware Safe. Your own dedicated hardware vault for keys — AWS can't touch them.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"CloudHSM is equivalent to on-premises HSM appliances (Thales Luna, SafeNet) used for high-security key management in financial services and government environments."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Penetration Testing Policy?","options":["AWS prohibits all penetration testing","AWS allows customers to conduct penetration testing on their own AWS resources without prior approval for most services","AWS requires a 6-month advance notice for all penetration testing","Penetration testing is only allowed with a Business support plan"],"correct_answer":"AWS allows customers to conduct penetration testing on their own AWS resources without prior approval for most services","explanation":"AWS allows customers to perform security assessments and penetration testing on their own AWS infrastructure without prior approval for most services. Some activities (like DDoS simulation) still require prior approval.","memory_technique":"AWS pen testing = test your own stuff freely. You own the resources, you can test them. Just don't attack AWS infrastructure itself.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"This is equivalent to a colocation provider allowing you to run vulnerability scans on your own servers — you can test what you own, but you can't attack the shared infrastructure."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon Detective?","options":["A service for detecting network intrusions","A service that analyses and visualises security data to investigate potential security issues","A compliance scanning service","A service for detecting malware on EC2 instances"],"correct_answer":"A service that analyses and visualises security data to investigate potential security issues","explanation":"Amazon Detective automatically collects log data from your AWS resources and uses machine learning to create interactive visualisations for security investigations, helping you quickly analyse and identify the root cause of security findings.","memory_technique":"Detective = Security investigator. When GuardDuty finds a threat, Detective helps you investigate the crime scene.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Amazon Detective is equivalent to a SIEM's investigation and forensics capabilities — it correlates events across multiple data sources to help security analysts understand the scope and impact of an incident."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of AWS Config Rules?","options":["To configure EC2 instances automatically","To evaluate whether AWS resources comply with desired configurations","To configure network routing rules","To manage IAM policy rules"],"correct_answer":"To evaluate whether AWS resources comply with desired configurations","explanation":"AWS Config Rules evaluate whether your AWS resources comply with desired configurations. AWS provides managed rules (e.g., 'S3 buckets must have encryption enabled') and you can create custom rules.","memory_technique":"Config Rules = Compliance checklist. Each rule checks one thing — like a building inspector checking each code requirement.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Config Rules are equivalent to compliance policy checks in configuration management tools like Chef InSpec or Puppet — automated verification that resources meet defined standards."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Shared Responsibility Model for Lambda?","options":["AWS manages everything including the code","The customer manages the OS and runtime","AWS manages the infrastructure, OS, and runtime; the customer manages the code, IAM permissions, and data","The customer manages the infrastructure; AWS manages the code"],"correct_answer":"AWS manages the infrastructure, OS, and runtime; the customer manages the code, IAM permissions, and data","explanation":"For Lambda (serverless), AWS manages the physical infrastructure, OS, and language runtime. Customers are responsible for their function code, IAM execution roles, and the data processed.","memory_technique":"Serverless = AWS manages even more. Lambda: AWS manages everything below your code. You just write the function.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"This is equivalent to using a fully managed application hosting service — the provider manages the entire stack below your application code."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of IAM Permission Boundaries?","options":["To set the maximum permissions an IAM entity can have","To grant additional permissions beyond what policies allow","To restrict access to specific AWS Regions","To manage billing permissions"],"correct_answer":"To set the maximum permissions an IAM entity can have","explanation":"IAM Permission Boundaries set the maximum permissions that an IAM entity (user or role) can have. Even if an identity-based policy grants more permissions, the boundary limits what can actually be used.","memory_technique":"Permission Boundary = fence around your permissions. You can only go as far as the fence, even if your policy says you can go further.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Permission Boundaries are equivalent to privilege delegation controls in PAM (Privileged Access Management) systems — they prevent privilege escalation by capping the maximum permissions a delegated admin can grant."},
]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# TECHNOLOGY — Difficulty 3
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
questions += [
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between Amazon SNS and Amazon SQS?","options":["SNS is a queue; SQS is a pub/sub service","SNS is a pub/sub service that pushes to multiple subscribers; SQS is a queue where consumers pull messages","They are identical","SNS is for email only; SQS is for all message types"],"correct_answer":"SNS is a pub/sub service that pushes to multiple subscribers; SQS is a queue where consumers pull messages","explanation":"SNS (pub/sub) pushes messages to all subscribers simultaneously. SQS (queue) holds messages until a consumer polls and retrieves them. They are often combined: SNS fan-out to multiple SQS queues.","memory_technique":"SNS = Shout (broadcast to many). SQS = Suggestion box (one consumer picks up each message). SNS fans out; SQS lines up.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"SNS is equivalent to a publish-subscribe message broker (ActiveMQ topics). SQS is equivalent to a point-to-point queue (ActiveMQ queues or IBM MQ)."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon EKS?","options":["A managed container registry","A managed Kubernetes service","A serverless container service","A virtual machine service"],"correct_answer":"A managed Kubernetes service","explanation":"Amazon EKS (Elastic Kubernetes Service) is a managed Kubernetes service that makes it easy to run Kubernetes on AWS without needing to install and operate your own Kubernetes control plane.","memory_technique":"EKS = Elastic Kubernetes Service. K8s managed by AWS — you get the power of Kubernetes without managing the control plane.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"EKS replaces self-managed Kubernetes clusters on VMs. Instead of managing etcd, API servers, and controller managers, AWS handles the control plane."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between Amazon ECS and Amazon EKS?","options":["ECS uses Docker; EKS uses Kubernetes","ECS is AWS's proprietary container orchestration; EKS is managed Kubernetes","ECS is serverless; EKS requires EC2 instances","They are the same service"],"correct_answer":"ECS is AWS's proprietary container orchestration; EKS is managed Kubernetes","explanation":"ECS is AWS's own container orchestration service with a simpler learning curve. EKS runs Kubernetes, which is the industry-standard container orchestration platform with a larger ecosystem.","memory_technique":"ECS = AWS's own system (simpler). EKS = Kubernetes (industry standard, more complex). Choose ECS for simplicity, EKS for Kubernetes compatibility.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"ECS is like a proprietary orchestration platform; EKS is like running standard Kubernetes. If you're already using Kubernetes on-premises, EKS provides a familiar migration path."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Step Functions?","options":["A service for managing Lambda function versions","A serverless workflow orchestration service for coordinating distributed applications","A CI/CD pipeline service","A service for managing API Gateway steps"],"correct_answer":"A serverless workflow orchestration service for coordinating distributed applications","explanation":"AWS Step Functions is a serverless workflow service that lets you coordinate multiple AWS services into serverless workflows. It manages state, handles errors, and retries automatically.","memory_technique":"Step Functions = Choreographer for your services. Coordinates the steps of a workflow like a dance choreographer.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Step Functions replaces custom workflow engines and state machines. It's equivalent to BPM (Business Process Management) tools or workflow orchestration platforms like Apache Airflow."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon API Gateway?","options":["A network gateway for VPCs","A fully managed service for creating, publishing, and managing APIs","A DNS gateway service","A load balancer for APIs"],"correct_answer":"A fully managed service for creating, publishing, and managing APIs","explanation":"Amazon API Gateway is a fully managed service that makes it easy to create, publish, maintain, monitor, and secure APIs. It handles traffic management, authorisation, monitoring, and API versioning.","memory_technique":"API Gateway = Front door for your APIs. All API requests come through the gateway, which handles auth, throttling, and routing.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"API Gateway replaces traditional API management platforms like Apigee or MuleSoft. It provides the same capabilities (rate limiting, auth, versioning) in a fully managed service."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon CloudWatch?","options":["A service for recording API calls","A monitoring and observability service for AWS resources and applications","A log storage service","A network monitoring service"],"correct_answer":"A monitoring and observability service for AWS resources and applications","explanation":"Amazon CloudWatch collects monitoring and operational data in the form of logs, metrics, and events. It provides a unified view of AWS resources, applications, and services.","memory_technique":"CloudWatch = Cloud Watchman. Monitors everything in your AWS environment — metrics, logs, alarms, dashboards.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"CloudWatch replaces traditional monitoring tools like Nagios, Zabbix, or PRTG. It provides the same metrics collection and alerting capabilities natively integrated with all AWS services."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS CodePipeline?","options":["A code repository service","A fully managed continuous delivery service for automating release pipelines","A code review service","A testing service"],"correct_answer":"A fully managed continuous delivery service for automating release pipelines","explanation":"AWS CodePipeline is a fully managed continuous delivery service that automates the build, test, and deploy phases of your release process every time there is a code change.","memory_technique":"CodePipeline = Assembly line for code. Code goes in one end, deployed application comes out the other.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"CodePipeline replaces Jenkins or GitLab CI/CD pipelines. It provides the same pipeline automation capabilities as a fully managed AWS service."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon ECR?","options":["A container orchestration service","A fully managed container image registry","A serverless container service","A container monitoring service"],"correct_answer":"A fully managed container image registry","explanation":"Amazon ECR (Elastic Container Registry) is a fully managed Docker container image registry. It integrates with ECS, EKS, and Lambda for seamless container image deployment.","memory_technique":"ECR = Elastic Container Registry. Like Docker Hub but managed by AWS and integrated with your AWS services.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"ECR replaces self-hosted Docker registries (Harbor, Nexus) or Docker Hub for storing container images. It provides the same registry functionality with AWS IAM integration."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS DataSync?","options":["A database synchronisation service","A service for automating data transfer between on-premises storage and AWS storage services","A real-time data streaming service","A database replication service"],"correct_answer":"A service for automating data transfer between on-premises storage and AWS storage services","explanation":"AWS DataSync is an online data transfer service that simplifies, automates, and accelerates moving data between on-premises storage and AWS storage services like S3, EFS, and FSx.","memory_technique":"DataSync = Data Synchroniser. Automatically syncs data between your on-premises storage and AWS — like rsync but managed and accelerated.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"DataSync replaces manual rsync scripts or third-party data migration tools. It provides automated, scheduled data transfer with built-in integrity verification."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon FSx?","options":["A managed object storage service","A managed file system service supporting Windows File Server and Lustre","A managed block storage service","A managed database service"],"correct_answer":"A managed file system service supporting Windows File Server and Lustre","explanation":"Amazon FSx provides fully managed third-party file systems. FSx for Windows File Server provides native Windows file system features; FSx for Lustre provides high-performance computing file systems.","memory_technique":"FSx = File System X (for various file systems). FSx for Windows = managed Windows file server. FSx for Lustre = managed HPC file system.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"FSx for Windows replaces on-premises Windows file servers (DFS shares). It provides the same SMB protocol and Active Directory integration without managing the underlying Windows Server infrastructure."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Transit Gateway?","options":["A service for connecting to the internet","A network transit hub that connects VPCs and on-premises networks","A DNS routing service","A VPN endpoint service"],"correct_answer":"A network transit hub that connects VPCs and on-premises networks","explanation":"AWS Transit Gateway acts as a cloud router, connecting multiple VPCs and on-premises networks through a central hub. It simplifies network architecture by replacing complex VPC peering meshes.","memory_technique":"Transit Gateway = Cloud router hub. Like a central train station — all routes go through the hub instead of direct point-to-point connections.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Transit Gateway replaces complex VPC peering meshes and hub-and-spoke VPN configurations. It's equivalent to a core router in a traditional hub-and-spoke WAN architecture."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon Lightsail?","options":["A simplified cloud platform for deploying virtual servers, databases, and applications with predictable pricing","A serverless compute service","A managed Kubernetes service","A content delivery network"],"correct_answer":"A simplified cloud platform for deploying virtual servers, databases, and applications with predictable pricing","explanation":"Amazon Lightsail is designed for simpler workloads and developers who need a straightforward cloud platform. It provides virtual servers, databases, storage, and networking with simple, predictable pricing.","memory_technique":"Lightsail = Lightweight AWS. Simple, predictable pricing for simple workloads. Like a starter kit for cloud.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Lightsail is equivalent to traditional VPS hosting providers like DigitalOcean or Linode — simple, fixed-price virtual servers without the complexity of full AWS services."},
]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# BILLING AND PRICING — Difficulty 3
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
questions += [
  {"question_text":"A company runs a steady-state workload on EC2 for 3 years. Which pricing option provides the best cost optimisation?","options":["On-Demand Instances","Spot Instances","3-year All Upfront Reserved Instances","Dedicated Hosts"],"correct_answer":"3-year All Upfront Reserved Instances","explanation":"For steady-state workloads running continuously for 3 years, 3-year All Upfront Reserved Instances provide the maximum discount (up to 72% vs On-Demand). The predictable workload justifies the long-term commitment.","memory_technique":"Steady state + long term = Reserved. Like buying a house vs. renting — upfront cost, but maximum savings over time.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"This mirrors the decision to buy vs. lease servers. For known, stable workloads, purchasing (Reserved) beats renting (On-Demand) over a 3-year period."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between Compute Savings Plans and EC2 Instance Savings Plans?","options":["They are identical","EC2 Instance Savings Plans offer higher discounts but are locked to a specific instance family and region; Compute Savings Plans offer lower discounts but apply flexibly across EC2, Fargate, and Lambda","Compute Savings Plans only apply to Lambda","EC2 Instance Savings Plans require All Upfront payment"],"correct_answer":"EC2 Instance Savings Plans offer higher discounts but are locked to a specific instance family and region; Compute Savings Plans offer lower discounts but apply flexibly across EC2, Fargate, and Lambda","explanation":"EC2 Instance Savings Plans provide deeper discounts (up to 72%) but are committed to a specific instance family in a specific region. Compute Savings Plans provide slightly lower discounts (up to 66%) but apply automatically across any EC2 instance family, size, OS, region, Fargate, and Lambda.","memory_technique":"EC2 Instance SP = Specific seat reservation (deeper discount, less flexible). Compute SP = Flexible open ticket (slightly less discount, works anywhere).","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"This is analogous to choosing between a specific-model server lease (locked to one SKU, better price) vs. a flexible compute capacity agreement (any server type, slightly higher rate)."},
  {"question_text":"A company has unpredictable traffic spikes. Which combination of EC2 pricing is most cost-effective?","options":["All On-Demand","All Reserved Instances","Reserved Instances for baseline load + On-Demand or Spot for spikes","All Spot Instances"],"correct_answer":"Reserved Instances for baseline load + On-Demand or Spot for spikes","explanation":"The optimal strategy is Reserved Instances for the predictable baseline load (maximising discount) and On-Demand or Spot for unpredictable spikes. This balances cost savings with flexibility.","memory_technique":"Base + Burst strategy: Reserve your foundation (RI), rent extra floors when needed (On-Demand/Spot). Like owning a small office and renting conference rooms for big meetings.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"This mirrors traditional capacity planning: own/lease servers for baseline capacity, use burst hosting for peak periods — a hybrid approach common in enterprise IT."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Free Tier limit for Amazon EC2?","options":["100 hours per month of t2.micro or t3.micro","750 hours per month of t2.micro or t3.micro","Unlimited hours for the first month","24 hours per day of any instance type"],"correct_answer":"750 hours per month of t2.micro or t3.micro","explanation":"The AWS Free Tier includes 750 hours per month of t2.micro (or t3.micro in regions where t2.micro is not available) Linux or Windows instances for the first 12 months.","memory_technique":"750 hours = enough to run one instance 24/7 for a month (720 hours) with 30 hours to spare. Free Tier = one free micro instance.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"750 hours per month is equivalent to running one server continuously — the Free Tier gives you a free development or test server for the first year."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS data transfer pricing model?","options":["All data transfer is free","Data transfer into AWS is free; data transfer out of AWS to the internet incurs charges","All data transfer incurs charges","Data transfer is only charged between regions"],"correct_answer":"Data transfer into AWS is free; data transfer out of AWS to the internet incurs charges","explanation":"AWS charges for data transferred out of AWS to the internet (egress). Data transferred into AWS (ingress) is generally free. Data transfer between AWS services in the same region is also generally free.","memory_technique":"AWS = Hotel California. Checking in (ingress) is free; checking out (egress) costs money.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"This mirrors traditional hosting pricing where bandwidth is charged for outbound traffic. Enterprises often underestimate egress costs when migrating to cloud."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of AWS Cost Categories?","options":["To categorise EC2 instances by type","To group AWS costs into meaningful business categories for reporting","To categorise security findings","To organise IAM users into groups"],"correct_answer":"To group AWS costs into meaningful business categories for reporting","explanation":"AWS Cost Categories allow you to map your AWS costs into meaningful categories based on rules you define. For example, you can create a 'Production' category that includes all resources tagged with Environment=Production.","memory_technique":"Cost Categories = Custom cost buckets. Group your costs the way your business thinks about them, not just by AWS service.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Cost Categories are equivalent to custom cost centre hierarchies in ERP systems — they let you organise cloud costs to match your organisational structure."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Pricing Calculator's primary use case?","options":["Tracking current AWS spending","Estimating the cost of a new AWS architecture before deployment","Setting spending alerts","Analysing historical cost trends"],"correct_answer":"Estimating the cost of a new AWS architecture before deployment","explanation":"The AWS Pricing Calculator is used to estimate the cost of AWS services before you deploy them. You configure the services you plan to use and it calculates the estimated monthly cost.","memory_technique":"Pricing Calculator = Pre-purchase price check. Like getting a quote before buying — estimate costs before committing.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"The Pricing Calculator replaces the manual process of building cost models in spreadsheets when evaluating new infrastructure investments."},
  {"question_text":"What happens to Reserved Instance discounts when using AWS Organizations with Consolidated Billing?","options":["Reserved Instance discounts only apply to the account that purchased them","Reserved Instance discounts are automatically shared across all accounts in the organisation","Reserved Instance discounts must be manually transferred between accounts","Reserved Instance discounts are doubled when shared"],"correct_answer":"Reserved Instance discounts are automatically shared across all accounts in the organisation","explanation":"With Consolidated Billing, Reserved Instance and Savings Plans discounts are automatically shared across all accounts in the organisation. If one account's RI is not fully utilised, the discount applies to matching usage in other accounts.","memory_technique":"Consolidated Billing = RI sharing pool. Unused RI capacity in one account automatically benefits other accounts in the organisation.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"This is equivalent to enterprise licence agreements where unused licences in one department can be used by another — maximising the value of committed purchases."},
  {"question_text":"What is the S3 storage class with the lowest cost for data that is rarely accessed and can tolerate retrieval times of minutes to hours?","options":["S3 Standard","S3 Standard-IA","S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval","S3 Intelligent-Tiering"],"correct_answer":"S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval","explanation":"S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval (formerly S3 Glacier) is designed for data archiving with retrieval times of minutes to hours. It offers very low storage costs but charges for retrieval.","memory_technique":"Glacier = frozen archive. Data is frozen (cheap to store), but takes time to thaw (retrieve). Minutes to hours = Flexible Retrieval.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval replaces tape archives and offsite backup storage. It provides the same long-term archival capability at a fraction of the cost of physical media."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between S3 Standard and S3 Standard-IA?","options":["S3 Standard-IA is faster than S3 Standard","S3 Standard is for frequently accessed data; S3 Standard-IA is for infrequently accessed data with lower storage cost but retrieval fees","S3 Standard-IA has higher durability","They are the same storage class"],"correct_answer":"S3 Standard is for frequently accessed data; S3 Standard-IA is for infrequently accessed data with lower storage cost but retrieval fees","explanation":"S3 Standard is optimised for frequently accessed data with no retrieval fees. S3 Standard-IA (Infrequent Access) has lower storage costs but charges a retrieval fee, making it cost-effective for data accessed less than once a month.","memory_technique":"IA = Infrequent Access. Cheaper to store, costs to retrieve. Like a storage unit — cheaper than your house, but you pay to get your stuff out.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"S3 Standard-IA is equivalent to nearline storage in traditional storage tiering — cheaper than primary storage but with a small access penalty."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Budgets Actions feature?","options":["A feature that automatically deletes resources when budget is exceeded","A feature that can automatically apply IAM policies or stop EC2/RDS instances when a budget threshold is breached","A feature that sends budget reports to stakeholders","A feature that forecasts future budget needs"],"correct_answer":"A feature that can automatically apply IAM policies or stop EC2/RDS instances when a budget threshold is breached","explanation":"AWS Budgets Actions allows you to define automated responses when a budget threshold is breached — such as applying an IAM policy to restrict spending, stopping EC2 instances, or stopping RDS instances.","memory_technique":"Budgets Actions = Automatic spending brake. When you hit the limit, AWS automatically applies the brakes (stops instances or restricts permissions).","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Budgets Actions is equivalent to automated cost controls in enterprise financial systems — automatic enforcement actions when spending limits are exceeded."},
]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# CLOUD CONCEPTS — Difficulty 4
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
questions += [
  {"question_text":"A company needs a disaster recovery strategy with RTO of 15 minutes and RPO of 1 hour at the lowest cost. Which strategy is most appropriate?","options":["Backup and Restore","Pilot Light","Warm Standby","Multi-Site Active-Active"],"correct_answer":"Warm Standby","explanation":"Warm Standby maintains a scaled-down but fully functional copy of the production environment. It can be scaled up quickly to meet production load, achieving RTO of minutes. Pilot Light has longer RTO; Multi-Site is more expensive.","memory_technique":"Warm Standby = Warm engine idling. Ready to go in minutes, not hours. Pilot Light = Just the pilot flame — needs time to heat up.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Warm Standby mirrors traditional DR hot-standby configurations — a secondary site running at reduced capacity, ready to scale up. It's the cloud equivalent of a warm DR site."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Well-Architected Framework's Reliability pillar primarily concerned with?","options":["Reducing costs","Ensuring a workload performs its intended function correctly and consistently","Protecting data and systems","Optimising resource utilisation"],"correct_answer":"Ensuring a workload performs its intended function correctly and consistently","explanation":"The Reliability pillar focuses on the ability of a workload to recover from failures, dynamically acquire computing resources to meet demand, and mitigate disruptions such as misconfigurations or transient network issues.","memory_technique":"Reliability = Dependability. Will it work when you need it? Focuses on recovery, redundancy, and resilience.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"The Reliability pillar maps to traditional IT concepts of high availability, disaster recovery, and business continuity planning."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Well-Architected Framework's Operational Excellence pillar primarily concerned with?","options":["Reducing infrastructure costs","Running and monitoring systems to deliver business value and continually improving processes","Protecting data from unauthorised access","Maximising application performance"],"correct_answer":"Running and monitoring systems to deliver business value and continually improving processes","explanation":"Operational Excellence focuses on running and monitoring systems to deliver business value, and continually improving supporting processes and procedures. Key topics include automation, responding to events, and defining standards.","memory_technique":"Operational Excellence = Running the business well. Automate, monitor, improve. Like a well-run factory floor.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Operational Excellence maps to ITIL Service Operations and Continual Service Improvement — the processes for running IT services effectively and improving them over time."},
  {"question_text":"A company wants to migrate their on-premises application to AWS with minimal changes. Which migration strategy does this represent?","options":["Re-architect","Re-platform","Rehost (Lift and Shift)","Retire"],"correct_answer":"Rehost (Lift and Shift)","explanation":"Rehosting (Lift and Shift) involves moving applications to AWS without making any changes. The application runs on EC2 instances in the same configuration as on-premises, just in the cloud.","memory_technique":"Lift and Shift = Pick up the server and move it to AWS. No changes, just a new location.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Lift and shift is the fastest migration approach — equivalent to physically moving servers to a colocation facility. It provides immediate cloud benefits (elasticity, managed hardware) without application changes."},
  {"question_text":"What are the 7 Rs of cloud migration?","options":["Rehost, Replatform, Repurchase, Refactor, Retire, Retain, Relocate","Replace, Rebuild, Reuse, Retire, Retain, Relocate, Rehost","Rehost, Rebuild, Replace, Retire, Retain, Relocate, Replatform","Refactor, Rehost, Replatform, Repurchase, Retire, Retain, Relocate"],"correct_answer":"Rehost, Replatform, Repurchase, Refactor, Retire, Retain, Relocate","explanation":"The 7 Rs are migration strategies: Rehost (lift and shift), Replatform (lift, tinker, and shift), Repurchase (move to SaaS), Refactor/Re-architect (redesign for cloud), Retire (decommission), Retain (keep on-premises), Relocate (move to cloud without changes at hypervisor level).","memory_technique":"7 Rs: Rehost, Replatform, Repurchase, Refactor, Retire, Retain, Relocate. Remember: 'Really Practical People Rarely Retire, Remaining Relevant.'","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"The 7 Rs provide a decision framework for each application in a migration portfolio — similar to the application rationalisation process in traditional IT portfolio management."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Cloud Adoption Framework (CAF) Security perspective primarily focused on?","options":["Reducing security costs","Ensuring the organisation meets its security and compliance objectives in the cloud","Automating security testing","Managing security vendor relationships"],"correct_answer":"Ensuring the organisation meets its security and compliance objectives in the cloud","explanation":"The CAF Security perspective helps organisations achieve the security outcomes and capabilities needed to meet their security and compliance objectives in the cloud, covering identity, infrastructure, data, and application security.","memory_technique":"CAF Security perspective = Security roadmap for cloud adoption. Covers all security domains needed for a secure cloud journey.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"The CAF Security perspective maps to traditional security frameworks like ISO 27001 or NIST CSF — providing a structured approach to security governance during cloud transformation."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between AWS CloudFormation and AWS CDK?","options":["They are the same service","CloudFormation uses JSON/YAML templates; CDK allows you to define infrastructure using familiar programming languages","CloudFormation is for EC2 only; CDK is for all services","CDK is deprecated in favour of CloudFormation"],"correct_answer":"CloudFormation uses JSON/YAML templates; CDK allows you to define infrastructure using familiar programming languages","explanation":"AWS CloudFormation uses JSON or YAML templates. The AWS CDK (Cloud Development Kit) allows you to define cloud infrastructure using familiar programming languages (TypeScript, Python, Java, C#) that compile to CloudFormation templates.","memory_technique":"CloudFormation = YAML/JSON blueprints. CDK = Write infrastructure in Python/TypeScript. CDK generates CloudFormation under the hood.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"CDK is equivalent to using a high-level programming language instead of raw configuration files — like writing Terraform in Python instead of HCL, with the same underlying execution engine."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Global Accelerator?","options":["A CDN service for caching content","A service that improves application availability and performance using the AWS global network","A DNS routing service","A load balancer for global applications"],"correct_answer":"A service that improves application availability and performance using the AWS global network","explanation":"AWS Global Accelerator improves the availability and performance of applications by routing traffic through the AWS global network instead of the public internet, reducing latency and improving reliability.","memory_technique":"Global Accelerator = Express lane on the AWS highway. Your traffic travels on AWS's private network instead of the congested public internet.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Global Accelerator is equivalent to using a private MPLS network instead of the public internet for application traffic — more reliable and lower latency than internet routing."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Well-Architected Framework's Performance Efficiency pillar primarily concerned with?","options":["Reducing costs","Using computing resources efficiently to meet system requirements and maintaining efficiency as demand changes","Protecting data and systems","Ensuring system reliability"],"correct_answer":"Using computing resources efficiently to meet system requirements and maintaining efficiency as demand changes","explanation":"Performance Efficiency focuses on using computing resources efficiently to meet system requirements and maintaining that efficiency as demand changes and technologies evolve.","memory_technique":"Performance Efficiency = Right tool, right size, right time. Use the most efficient resource for each workload.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Performance Efficiency maps to traditional IT capacity management and technology refresh cycles — ensuring you're using the right technology at the right scale."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Sustainability pillar of the Well-Architected Framework?","options":["A pillar focused on financial sustainability","A pillar focused on minimising the environmental impact of cloud workloads","A pillar focused on sustainable business practices","A pillar focused on long-term architectural sustainability"],"correct_answer":"A pillar focused on minimising the environmental impact of cloud workloads","explanation":"The Sustainability pillar (the sixth pillar, added in 2021) focuses on minimising the environmental impacts of running cloud workloads, including energy consumption and carbon footprint.","memory_technique":"Sustainability = Green cloud. Use only what you need, choose efficient services, reduce your carbon footprint.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"The Sustainability pillar maps to corporate ESG (Environmental, Social, Governance) initiatives — measuring and reducing the environmental impact of IT operations."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Migration Hub?","options":["A physical hub for connecting on-premises networks to AWS","A central location for tracking the progress of application migrations to AWS","A service for migrating databases","A tool for estimating migration costs"],"correct_answer":"A central location for tracking the progress of application migrations to AWS","explanation":"AWS Migration Hub provides a single location to track the progress of application migrations across multiple AWS and partner migration tools. It gives visibility into the status of each migration.","memory_technique":"Migration Hub = Mission Control for migrations. One dashboard showing the status of all your migration projects.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Migration Hub is equivalent to a project management dashboard for IT migrations — providing centralised visibility across multiple workstreams and tools."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Application Discovery Service?","options":["A service for discovering new AWS services","A service that helps plan migrations by collecting data about on-premises servers and their dependencies","A service for discovering security vulnerabilities","A service for discovering unused AWS resources"],"correct_answer":"A service that helps plan migrations by collecting data about on-premises servers and their dependencies","explanation":"AWS Application Discovery Service helps enterprise customers plan migration projects by gathering information about their on-premises data centers, including server configurations, performance data, and application dependencies.","memory_technique":"Application Discovery = Migration detective. Discovers what you have on-premises before you move it to AWS.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Application Discovery Service replaces manual CMDB population and dependency mapping exercises. It's equivalent to running a discovery tool like ServiceNow Discovery or Flexera to inventory your estate."},
]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SECURITY AND COMPLIANCE — Difficulty 4
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
questions += [
  {"question_text":"A company needs to enforce that all S3 buckets must have server-side encryption enabled. Which AWS service can automatically detect and remediate non-compliant resources?","options":["AWS CloudTrail","AWS Config with remediation actions","Amazon GuardDuty","AWS Trusted Advisor"],"correct_answer":"AWS Config with remediation actions","explanation":"AWS Config continuously monitors resource configurations. Config Rules evaluate compliance. With SSM Automation remediation actions, Config can automatically fix non-compliant resources like enabling S3 encryption.","memory_technique":"Config = Configuration Police. It watches for rule violations and can automatically issue 'tickets' (remediation) to fix them.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"AWS Config with remediation is equivalent to enterprise configuration management tools like Chef, Puppet, or Ansible combined with compliance scanning — it detects drift and auto-corrects."},
  {"question_text":"A company uses AWS Organizations. They need to prevent any account from disabling CloudTrail. Which feature enforces this?","options":["IAM Permission Boundaries","AWS Config Rules","Service Control Policies (SCPs)","AWS Control Tower Guardrails"],"correct_answer":"Service Control Policies (SCPs)","explanation":"SCPs in AWS Organizations define the maximum permissions for accounts in an OU. An SCP can deny the cloudtrail:StopLogging action across all accounts, and even account administrators cannot override it.","memory_technique":"SCP = Supreme Court Policy. Even account admins can't override it — it's the highest law in the AWS Organization.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"SCPs are equivalent to Group Policy Objects (GPOs) in Active Directory at the domain level — they set boundaries that override local administrator settings across all managed accounts."},
  {"question_text":"What is cross-account access in AWS and how is it implemented?","options":["Accessing resources in another AWS account using shared credentials","Accessing resources in another AWS account by assuming an IAM role in that account","Accessing resources in another AWS account using VPC peering","Cross-account access is not possible in AWS"],"correct_answer":"Accessing resources in another AWS account by assuming an IAM role in that account","explanation":"Cross-account access is implemented by creating an IAM role in the target account that trusts the source account, and granting the source account permission to assume that role. The role provides temporary credentials for accessing the target account's resources.","memory_technique":"Cross-account = Two-door lock. Target account creates a role (door 1); source account gets permission to assume it (door 2). Both doors must be unlocked.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Cross-account access mirrors inter-domain trust relationships in Active Directory. Both the trusting domain (resource) and the trusted domain (identity) must explicitly allow the access."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between AWS KMS Customer Managed Keys (CMKs) and AWS Managed Keys?","options":["They are the same","Customer Managed Keys give you full control over key policies and rotation; AWS Managed Keys are created and managed by AWS on your behalf","AWS Managed Keys are more secure","Customer Managed Keys are free; AWS Managed Keys cost money"],"correct_answer":"Customer Managed Keys give you full control over key policies and rotation; AWS Managed Keys are created and managed by AWS on your behalf","explanation":"Customer Managed Keys (CMKs) give you full control — you define key policies, enable/disable keys, and control rotation. AWS Managed Keys are created and managed by AWS for use with specific services; you have limited control.","memory_technique":"CMK = Your key, your rules. AWS Managed Key = AWS's key, AWS's rules. CMK = custom lock; AWS Managed = standard lock.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"CMKs are equivalent to managing your own HSM keys; AWS Managed Keys are equivalent to using a service provider's default encryption — convenient but less control."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Firewall Manager?","options":["A service for managing EC2 security groups","A central service for managing AWS WAF rules, Shield Advanced protections, and security groups across multiple accounts","A network firewall service","A service for managing VPC firewall rules"],"correct_answer":"A central service for managing AWS WAF rules, Shield Advanced protections, and security groups across multiple accounts","explanation":"AWS Firewall Manager is a security management service that allows you to centrally configure and manage firewall rules across your accounts and applications in AWS Organizations.","memory_technique":"Firewall Manager = Central firewall command. One place to manage WAF rules, Shield, and security groups across all your accounts.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Firewall Manager is equivalent to a centralised firewall management platform (like Cisco Security Manager or Palo Alto Panorama) — one console to manage security policies across all your network devices."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of AWS Resource Access Manager (RAM)?","options":["To manage EC2 instance resources","To securely share AWS resources across AWS accounts or within an AWS Organisation","To manage IAM resource policies","To monitor resource utilisation"],"correct_answer":"To securely share AWS resources across AWS accounts or within an AWS Organisation","explanation":"AWS RAM allows you to share AWS resources with other AWS accounts or within your AWS Organisation. Resources like VPC subnets, Transit Gateways, and Route 53 Resolver rules can be shared.","memory_technique":"RAM = Resource Access Manager. Share resources between accounts without duplicating them — like sharing a printer on a network.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"RAM is equivalent to shared resource pools in traditional IT — centralised infrastructure (like a shared network segment) that multiple teams or business units can use without each maintaining their own."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Security Token Service (STS)?","options":["A service for managing SSL/TLS certificates","A service that provides temporary, limited-privilege credentials for AWS resources","A service for storing security tokens","A two-factor authentication service"],"correct_answer":"A service that provides temporary, limited-privilege credentials for AWS resources","explanation":"AWS STS enables you to request temporary, limited-privilege credentials for IAM users or federated users. These credentials expire after a configurable period, reducing the risk of long-term credential exposure.","memory_technique":"STS = Short-Term Security. Provides temporary credentials that expire — like a visitor badge vs. a permanent employee badge.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"STS is equivalent to a PAM (Privileged Access Management) system that issues time-limited privileged credentials — reducing the risk of permanent credential exposure."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of AWS PrivateLink?","options":["A private VPN connection to AWS","A service that provides private connectivity between VPCs and AWS services without exposing traffic to the public internet","A private DNS service","A private content delivery network"],"correct_answer":"A service that provides private connectivity between VPCs and AWS services without exposing traffic to the public internet","explanation":"AWS PrivateLink provides private connectivity between VPCs, AWS services, and on-premises applications without exposing traffic to the public internet. It uses interface VPC endpoints.","memory_technique":"PrivateLink = Private tunnel. Traffic stays on AWS's private network — never touches the public internet.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"PrivateLink is equivalent to using a private MPLS circuit instead of the internet to access a SaaS service — the traffic stays on a private network, reducing exposure."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between a VPC endpoint and AWS PrivateLink?","options":["They are the same thing","Gateway endpoints are for S3 and DynamoDB; Interface endpoints (PrivateLink) are for other AWS services","VPC endpoints are for on-premises connectivity; PrivateLink is for VPC-to-VPC","Gateway endpoints use PrivateLink; Interface endpoints use VPN"],"correct_answer":"Gateway endpoints are for S3 and DynamoDB; Interface endpoints (PrivateLink) are for other AWS services","explanation":"There are two types of VPC endpoints: Gateway endpoints (for S3 and DynamoDB, free) and Interface endpoints (powered by PrivateLink, for most other AWS services, charged per hour and per GB).","memory_technique":"Gateway endpoint = free S3/DynamoDB shortcut. Interface endpoint (PrivateLink) = private tunnel to other AWS services (costs money).","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Gateway endpoints are like a direct route to specific destinations; Interface endpoints are like a private tunnel to any destination — both avoid the public internet but work differently."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Nitro System?","options":["A type of EC2 instance","The underlying platform for EC2 instances that offloads virtualisation functions to dedicated hardware","A security scanning service","A network acceleration service"],"correct_answer":"The underlying platform for EC2 instances that offloads virtualisation functions to dedicated hardware","explanation":"The AWS Nitro System is the underlying platform for EC2 instances. It offloads virtualisation functions (networking, storage, security) to dedicated hardware and software, improving performance and security.","memory_technique":"Nitro = Nitro boost for EC2. Dedicated hardware handles the boring virtualisation work, freeing the CPU for your workload.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"The Nitro System is equivalent to SmartNICs and DPUs (Data Processing Units) in modern data center hardware — offloading network and storage processing from the main CPU to dedicated chips."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of AWS IAM Access Analyzer?","options":["To analyse IAM policy performance","To identify resources that are shared with external entities or are publicly accessible","To analyse IAM user activity","To optimise IAM policy size"],"correct_answer":"To identify resources that are shared with external entities or are publicly accessible","explanation":"AWS IAM Access Analyzer helps identify resources in your organisation and accounts that are shared with an external entity. It analyses resource-based policies to find unintended public or cross-account access.","memory_technique":"Access Analyzer = Finds open doors. Scans your policies to find resources accidentally exposed to the public or other accounts.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"IAM Access Analyzer is equivalent to a network vulnerability scanner that finds open ports — it finds open access paths in your IAM policies that you may not have intended."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Shared Responsibility Model for EC2?","options":["AWS manages everything","The customer manages everything","AWS manages the physical infrastructure and hypervisor; the customer manages the OS, applications, data, and security configuration","AWS manages the OS; the customer manages the applications"],"correct_answer":"AWS manages the physical infrastructure and hypervisor; the customer manages the OS, applications, data, and security configuration","explanation":"For EC2 (IaaS), AWS manages the physical hardware, data center facilities, and hypervisor. Customers are responsible for the guest OS (including patches), applications, data, security groups, and IAM.","memory_technique":"EC2 = IaaS. AWS manages below the OS (hardware, hypervisor). You manage the OS and everything above it.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"This is equivalent to colocation hosting — the colo provider manages the building, power, and cooling; you manage your servers, OS, and applications."},
]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# TECHNOLOGY — Difficulty 4
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
questions += [
  {"question_text":"A company wants to migrate their on-premises MySQL database to AWS with minimal application changes. Which service is the best fit?","options":["Amazon DynamoDB","Amazon Redshift","Amazon RDS for MySQL","Amazon Aurora Serverless"],"correct_answer":"Amazon RDS for MySQL","explanation":"Amazon RDS for MySQL is a managed MySQL-compatible database that requires minimal application changes. It supports the same MySQL features, drivers, and tools, making lift-and-shift migrations straightforward.","memory_technique":"RDS for MySQL = Drop-in replacement. Same MySQL, managed by AWS. Lift and shift without rewriting your app.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"This is a classic rehosting migration pattern. RDS for MySQL is wire-compatible with on-premises MySQL, so existing applications connect without code changes."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of an Application Load Balancer (ALB) compared to a Network Load Balancer (NLB)?","options":["ALB operates at layer 4; NLB operates at layer 7","ALB operates at layer 7 and supports content-based routing; NLB operates at layer 4 for ultra-high performance","They are identical","ALB is for internal traffic; NLB is for external traffic"],"correct_answer":"ALB operates at layer 7 and supports content-based routing; NLB operates at layer 4 for ultra-high performance","explanation":"ALB (Application Load Balancer) operates at layer 7 and supports content-based routing (by URL path, host header, HTTP method). NLB (Network Load Balancer) operates at layer 4 for ultra-low latency and high throughput.","memory_technique":"ALB = Smart router (reads the content). NLB = Fast router (just looks at the address). ALB for web apps; NLB for high-performance TCP/UDP.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"ALB is equivalent to an application-aware load balancer (F5 BIG-IP with iRules); NLB is equivalent to a pure TCP load balancer optimised for throughput."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon Aurora Serverless?","options":["A serverless NoSQL database","An on-demand, auto-scaling configuration for Amazon Aurora that automatically starts, scales, and shuts down based on application needs","A serverless data warehouse","A serverless caching service"],"correct_answer":"An on-demand, auto-scaling configuration for Amazon Aurora that automatically starts, scales, and shuts down based on application needs","explanation":"Amazon Aurora Serverless is an on-demand, auto-scaling configuration for Aurora. The database automatically starts up, shuts down, and scales capacity based on application needs — ideal for infrequent or unpredictable workloads.","memory_technique":"Aurora Serverless = Database that sleeps when not needed. Scales from zero to handle traffic, then scales back to zero. Pay only when active.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Aurora Serverless is equivalent to a database that automatically hibernates when idle — like a server that powers off when not in use, saving costs for development or intermittent workloads."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between Amazon SQS Standard and SQS FIFO queues?","options":["Standard queues guarantee order; FIFO queues do not","FIFO queues guarantee exactly-once processing and strict ordering; Standard queues offer higher throughput but may deliver messages out of order or more than once","They are identical","Standard queues are for large messages; FIFO queues are for small messages"],"correct_answer":"FIFO queues guarantee exactly-once processing and strict ordering; Standard queues offer higher throughput but may deliver messages out of order or more than once","explanation":"SQS Standard queues offer maximum throughput and at-least-once delivery but may deliver messages out of order. FIFO queues guarantee exactly-once processing and strict first-in-first-out ordering, but with lower throughput limits.","memory_technique":"Standard = Fast but messy (may duplicate, may reorder). FIFO = Orderly queue (strict order, no duplicates). Choose based on whether order matters.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Standard queues are like a busy post office where letters might arrive out of order. FIFO queues are like a numbered ticket system — strict order guaranteed."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon MSK?","options":["A managed Kubernetes service","A fully managed Apache Kafka service","A managed streaming analytics service","A managed message queue service"],"correct_answer":"A fully managed Apache Kafka service","explanation":"Amazon MSK (Managed Streaming for Apache Kafka) is a fully managed service that makes it easy to build and run applications that use Apache Kafka to process streaming data.","memory_technique":"MSK = Managed Streaming Kafka. Drop-in managed Kafka — same API, no cluster management.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"MSK replaces self-managed Kafka clusters on EC2 or on-premises. It provides the same Kafka API compatibility while AWS handles broker management, ZooKeeper, and patching."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Lake Formation?","options":["A service for creating data lakes in S3","A service that simplifies building, securing, and managing data lakes with centralised access control","A data warehouse service","A real-time data streaming service"],"correct_answer":"A service that simplifies building, securing, and managing data lakes with centralised access control","explanation":"AWS Lake Formation simplifies building, securing, and managing data lakes. It provides centralised access control including column-level security, row-level filtering, and cross-account data sharing.","memory_technique":"Lake Formation = Lake Warden. Manages who can fish in which part of the lake, down to which type of fish (column-level security).","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Lake Formation replaces complex combinations of S3 policies, Glue catalog permissions, and Athena workgroups. It provides the centralised data governance that traditional data warehouses had built-in."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between Amazon RDS Multi-AZ and RDS Read Replicas?","options":["They are the same feature","Multi-AZ provides high availability with synchronous replication to a standby; Read Replicas provide read scalability with asynchronous replication","Multi-AZ is for read scaling; Read Replicas are for high availability","Multi-AZ is only for MySQL; Read Replicas are for all engines"],"correct_answer":"Multi-AZ provides high availability with synchronous replication to a standby; Read Replicas provide read scalability with asynchronous replication","explanation":"RDS Multi-AZ synchronously replicates to a standby instance in another AZ for automatic failover (HA). Read Replicas asynchronously replicate to one or more instances that can serve read traffic (performance scaling).","memory_technique":"Multi-AZ = Backup driver (takes over if primary crashes). Read Replica = Extra cashier (handles more customers). HA vs. performance.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Multi-AZ is equivalent to synchronous database mirroring for HA. Read Replicas are equivalent to read-only database replicas used to offload reporting queries from the primary."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Elastic MapReduce (EMR)?","options":["A managed Kafka service","A managed big data platform for processing large datasets using Apache Hadoop, Spark, and other frameworks","A managed ETL service","A managed data warehouse service"],"correct_answer":"A managed big data platform for processing large datasets using Apache Hadoop, Spark, and other frameworks","explanation":"Amazon EMR is a managed big data platform that simplifies running big data frameworks like Apache Hadoop, Spark, HBase, and Presto on AWS. It automatically provisions and configures the cluster.","memory_technique":"EMR = Elastic MapReduce. Big data processing at scale — Hadoop/Spark without managing the cluster.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"EMR replaces self-managed Hadoop clusters on bare metal or VMs. It provides the same big data processing capabilities without managing cluster provisioning, configuration, and scaling."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of Amazon CloudFront Origin Shield?","options":["A DDoS protection layer for CloudFront","An additional caching layer that reduces the load on your origin server","A security scanning service for CloudFront","A WAF integration for CloudFront"],"correct_answer":"An additional caching layer that reduces the load on your origin server","explanation":"CloudFront Origin Shield is an additional caching layer that sits between CloudFront edge locations and your origin. It consolidates requests to the origin, reducing origin load and improving cache hit ratios.","memory_technique":"Origin Shield = Shield for your origin server. Fewer requests reach your origin because Origin Shield caches more aggressively.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Origin Shield is equivalent to a regional CDN PoP that aggregates requests before forwarding to the origin — reducing origin load by consolidating cache misses from multiple edge locations."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS App Runner?","options":["A service for running mobile applications","A fully managed service for deploying containerised web applications and APIs without managing infrastructure","A CI/CD pipeline service","A serverless function service"],"correct_answer":"A fully managed service for deploying containerised web applications and APIs without managing infrastructure","explanation":"AWS App Runner is a fully managed service that makes it easy to deploy containerised web applications and APIs. You provide your container image or source code, and App Runner handles deployment, scaling, and load balancing.","memory_technique":"App Runner = Runs your app for you. Like Heroku for containers — just push your code/image and it runs.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"App Runner is equivalent to a PaaS container service like Google Cloud Run or Azure Container Apps — fully managed container hosting without Kubernetes complexity."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon Neptune?","options":["A managed relational database","A fully managed graph database service","A managed time-series database","A managed document database"],"correct_answer":"A fully managed graph database service","explanation":"Amazon Neptune is a fully managed graph database service that supports both Property Graph (Gremlin) and RDF (SPARQL) query languages. It's optimised for storing and querying highly connected data.","memory_technique":"Neptune = Network of connections (like the god of the sea connecting everything). Graph DB = relationship-first storage.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Neptune replaces self-managed graph databases like Neo4j or JanusGraph. It provides the same graph traversal capabilities without managing the underlying infrastructure."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon Timestream?","options":["A managed relational database","A fast, scalable, fully managed time-series database","A managed streaming service","A managed data warehouse"],"correct_answer":"A fast, scalable, fully managed time-series database","explanation":"Amazon Timestream is a fast, scalable, and serverless time-series database for IoT and operational applications. It automatically scales to adjust capacity and performance, and stores and analyses trillions of events per day.","memory_technique":"Timestream = Time-series stream. Optimised for data with timestamps — IoT sensors, metrics, logs over time.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Timestream replaces self-managed time-series databases like InfluxDB or TimescaleDB. It's optimised for the same use cases — IoT telemetry, application metrics, and operational data."},
]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# BILLING AND PRICING — Difficulty 4
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
questions += [
  {"question_text":"A FinOps team wants to allocate AWS costs to specific business units. Which AWS feature enables this?","options":["AWS Organizations","AWS Cost Categories","Resource Tags with Cost Allocation Tags","AWS Budgets Actions"],"correct_answer":"Resource Tags with Cost Allocation Tags","explanation":"Cost Allocation Tags allow you to tag AWS resources with key-value pairs (e.g., Department=Marketing). After activating tags as cost allocation tags in Billing, they appear in Cost Explorer and the CUR, enabling cost breakdown by business unit.","memory_technique":"Tags = Price labels on resources. Tag every resource with its owner/project, then your bill automatically breaks down by department.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Cost allocation tags are equivalent to cost center codes in enterprise financial systems. Just as IT chargebacks use cost center codes to allocate server costs, AWS tags enable the same chargeback model."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Cost Anomaly Detection service?","options":["A service that detects security anomalies","A service that uses machine learning to detect unusual spending patterns and alert you","A service that detects performance anomalies","A service that detects configuration anomalies"],"correct_answer":"A service that uses machine learning to detect unusual spending patterns and alert you","explanation":"AWS Cost Anomaly Detection uses machine learning to continuously monitor your cost and usage, detect unusual spending, and alert you via SNS. It can identify anomalies at the service, account, or cost category level.","memory_technique":"Cost Anomaly Detection = Spending smoke detector. Automatically alerts you when something unusual is burning through your budget.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Cost Anomaly Detection is equivalent to fraud detection systems in financial services — it uses ML to identify unusual patterns that might indicate a problem (misconfiguration, security breach, or unexpected usage)."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between AWS Budgets and AWS Cost Anomaly Detection?","options":["They are the same service","Budgets alerts on predefined thresholds; Cost Anomaly Detection uses ML to detect unexpected spending patterns","Budgets uses ML; Cost Anomaly Detection uses fixed thresholds","Budgets is for forecasting; Cost Anomaly Detection is for historical analysis"],"correct_answer":"Budgets alerts on predefined thresholds; Cost Anomaly Detection uses ML to detect unexpected spending patterns","explanation":"AWS Budgets requires you to define a threshold (e.g., alert when monthly spend exceeds $1000). Cost Anomaly Detection uses ML to automatically identify unusual spending without requiring predefined thresholds.","memory_technique":"Budgets = Speed limit sign (you set the limit). Anomaly Detection = Speed camera with AI (detects unusual driving patterns automatically).","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Budgets is like a manual spending alert; Anomaly Detection is like an automated fraud detection system — one requires configuration, the other learns your patterns automatically."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Pricing model for data transfer between AWS services in the same Region?","options":["Always free","Free for most services within the same Region","Charged at the standard data transfer rate","Charged only for transfers over 1GB"],"correct_answer":"Free for most services within the same Region","explanation":"Data transfer between AWS services within the same Region is generally free. For example, transferring data from EC2 to S3 in the same Region incurs no data transfer charges. Cross-Region transfers are charged.","memory_technique":"Same Region = Free highway. Cross-Region = Toll road. Keep your data in the same Region to avoid transfer costs.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"This is equivalent to free LAN traffic within a data center vs. charged WAN traffic between data centers — keeping workloads co-located reduces network costs."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Marketplace pricing model for SaaS products?","options":["All SaaS products are free","SaaS products can be priced as free, BYOL, pay-as-you-go, or contract pricing","All SaaS products use pay-as-you-go only","SaaS products are always billed annually"],"correct_answer":"SaaS products can be priced as free, BYOL, pay-as-you-go, or contract pricing","explanation":"AWS Marketplace SaaS products support multiple pricing models: Free, Bring Your Own Licence (BYOL), pay-as-you-go (usage-based), and contract pricing (annual or multi-year commitments).","memory_technique":"Marketplace pricing = menu of options. Free, BYOL, pay-per-use, or contract. Choose what fits your procurement model.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"AWS Marketplace pricing mirrors traditional software procurement models — free trials, existing licences, subscription, or enterprise agreements — but consolidated into your AWS bill."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Cost and Usage Report (CUR) and how is it typically used?","options":["A monthly invoice sent by email","A detailed dataset delivered to S3 that contains all AWS cost and usage data, typically analysed with Athena or a data warehouse","A real-time cost dashboard","A tool for setting cost alerts"],"correct_answer":"A detailed dataset delivered to S3 that contains all AWS cost and usage data, typically analysed with Athena or a data warehouse","explanation":"The CUR is the most granular AWS billing data available. It is delivered to an S3 bucket as CSV or Parquet files and is typically queried with Athena, loaded into Redshift, or processed by third-party FinOps tools.","memory_technique":"CUR = Raw billing data dump. Every resource, every hour, every charge. Needs a tool to make sense of it.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"The CUR is equivalent to a raw transaction log from an ERP system — detailed enough for any analysis but requires processing to extract insights."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Free Tier limit for Amazon S3?","options":["Unlimited storage for 12 months","5GB of S3 Standard storage, 20,000 GET requests, and 2,000 PUT requests per month for 12 months","1TB of S3 Standard storage for 12 months","Unlimited requests but limited to 1GB storage"],"correct_answer":"5GB of S3 Standard storage, 20,000 GET requests, and 2,000 PUT requests per month for 12 months","explanation":"The AWS Free Tier for S3 includes 5GB of S3 Standard storage, 20,000 GET requests, and 2,000 PUT requests per month for the first 12 months after account creation.","memory_technique":"S3 Free Tier = 5GB, 20K GETs, 2K PUTs. Enough for a small website or development project.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"5GB is roughly equivalent to a small file server — enough for development and testing but not production workloads."},
  {"question_text":"What is the pricing model for AWS Lambda?","options":["Fixed monthly fee per function","Pay per invocation and per GB-second of compute time","Pay per hour the function is deployed","Pay per line of code"],"correct_answer":"Pay per invocation and per GB-second of compute time","explanation":"Lambda pricing is based on the number of requests (invocations) and the duration of execution measured in GB-seconds (memory allocated × execution time). The first 1 million requests and 400,000 GB-seconds per month are free.","memory_technique":"Lambda = Pay per millisecond of work. No idle costs — you only pay when your code actually runs.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Lambda's pricing model is the ultimate pay-per-use — unlike EC2 where you pay for the server whether it's busy or idle, Lambda charges only for actual execution time."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Pricing model for Amazon RDS?","options":["Pay per query","Pay per instance-hour, storage, I/O, and data transfer","Fixed monthly fee per database","Pay per table"],"correct_answer":"Pay per instance-hour, storage, I/O, and data transfer","explanation":"RDS pricing includes: instance hours (based on instance type), storage (per GB-month), I/O requests (for magnetic storage), backup storage, and data transfer. Multi-AZ deployments cost approximately 2x single-AZ.","memory_technique":"RDS pricing = instance + storage + I/O + transfer. Multi-AZ = double the instance cost for the standby.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"RDS pricing mirrors traditional database hosting — you pay for the server (instance), disk (storage), and bandwidth (transfer). Multi-AZ adds the cost of the standby server."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Pricing model for Amazon CloudFront?","options":["Fixed monthly fee","Pay per GB of data transferred out and per HTTP request","Pay per edge location used","Pay per origin request only"],"correct_answer":"Pay per GB of data transferred out and per HTTP request","explanation":"CloudFront pricing is based on data transfer out (per GB, varying by region) and HTTP/HTTPS requests (per 10,000 requests). There is no charge for data transfer from AWS origins to CloudFront.","memory_technique":"CloudFront = Pay for delivery. Data transfer out (to users) + requests. No charge for the trip from your origin to CloudFront.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"CloudFront pricing mirrors traditional CDN pricing — you pay for bandwidth delivered to end users and the number of requests served, not for the caching infrastructure itself."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Pricing model for Amazon DynamoDB?","options":["Pay per table","Pay per read/write capacity unit or on-demand per request, plus storage","Fixed monthly fee","Pay per query"],"correct_answer":"Pay per read/write capacity unit or on-demand per request, plus storage","explanation":"DynamoDB offers two pricing modes: Provisioned (pay for reserved read/write capacity units per hour) and On-Demand (pay per request). Both modes charge for storage per GB-month.","memory_technique":"DynamoDB = Provisioned (reserve capacity, predictable cost) or On-Demand (pay per request, variable cost). Plus storage.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"DynamoDB's provisioned capacity is like reserving database IOPS in advance; on-demand is like paying per transaction. Choose based on whether your workload is predictable."},
]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ALL TOPICS — Difficulty 5
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
questions += [
  {"question_text":"A company needs to provide temporary AWS credentials to users authenticated through their corporate Active Directory with the least operational overhead. Which solution is best?","options":["Create IAM users for each AD user and sync passwords","AWS IAM Identity Center with AD Connector","AWS Cognito with SAML federation","Custom Lambda function to generate STS tokens"],"correct_answer":"AWS IAM Identity Center with AD Connector","explanation":"AWS IAM Identity Center integrates with Active Directory via AD Connector. Users authenticate with their AD credentials and receive temporary AWS credentials scoped to their assigned permission sets — no IAM user management required.","memory_technique":"IAM Identity Center = Corporate ID badge for AWS. Your existing AD badge gets you into AWS rooms based on your job role.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"This is federated identity management — the same pattern used when enterprises integrate their AD with SaaS applications via SAML. AWS IAM Identity Center is the SAML service provider side."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a multi-region active-active architecture for their RDS database with automatic failover and minimal replication lag. Which solution is best?","options":["RDS Multi-AZ with read replicas in another region","Amazon Aurora Global Database","RDS cross-region automated backups","DynamoDB Global Tables"],"correct_answer":"Amazon Aurora Global Database","explanation":"Amazon Aurora Global Database spans multiple AWS Regions with one primary Region handling writes and up to five secondary Regions for reads. It uses dedicated replication infrastructure with typical lag under 1 second and can promote a secondary region to primary in under 1 minute.","memory_technique":"Aurora Global = Global supercar. Replicates across continents in under 1 second — faster than any traditional replication solution.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Aurora Global Database replaces complex multi-site Oracle Data Guard or SQL Server Always On configurations. It provides sub-second cross-region replication that would require expensive dedicated WAN links traditionally."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to process streaming data from IoT sensors in real time and store results in S3. Which combination of services is most appropriate?","options":["Amazon SQS → Lambda → S3","Amazon Kinesis Data Streams → Kinesis Data Firehose → S3","Amazon SNS → SQS → RDS","AWS IoT Core → DynamoDB → Redshift"],"correct_answer":"Amazon Kinesis Data Streams → Kinesis Data Firehose → S3","explanation":"Kinesis Data Streams ingests real-time streaming data at high throughput. Kinesis Data Firehose automatically loads the streaming data into S3 with built-in batching, compression, and encryption — no custom consumer code needed.","memory_technique":"Kinesis = Kinetic energy (always moving data). Streams capture it, Firehose shoots it to S3 like a fire hose.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"This pattern replaces traditional ETL pipelines using Apache Kafka + custom consumers. Kinesis provides managed Kafka-like streaming with Firehose acting as a managed sink connector."},
  {"question_text":"A company is designing a microservices architecture on AWS. They need service-to-service communication with automatic retries, circuit breaking, and observability without modifying application code. Which service provides this?","options":["Amazon API Gateway","AWS App Mesh","AWS Cloud Map","Elastic Load Balancing"],"correct_answer":"AWS App Mesh","explanation":"AWS App Mesh is a service mesh that provides application-level networking for microservices. It uses Envoy proxy sidecars to handle retries, circuit breaking, traffic shaping, and observability without requiring application code changes.","memory_technique":"App Mesh = Safety net between services. The mesh handles failures (circuit breaker), retries, and visibility — your services just talk to each other.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"App Mesh is equivalent to Istio or Linkerd service meshes. It implements the same sidecar proxy pattern used in Kubernetes environments to add resilience and observability to microservices."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a zero-trust network architecture on AWS where workloads verify identity before communicating, regardless of network location. Which combination of services best supports this?","options":["VPC Security Groups and NACLs","AWS IAM with resource-based policies, AWS PrivateLink, and mutual TLS via ACM Private CA","AWS WAF and AWS Shield","VPC Peering with strict route tables"],"correct_answer":"AWS IAM with resource-based policies, AWS PrivateLink, and mutual TLS via ACM Private CA","explanation":"Zero-trust requires identity verification for every request regardless of network location. IAM resource-based policies enforce identity-based authorisation. PrivateLink provides private connectivity. ACM Private CA enables mutual TLS for service-to-service authentication.","memory_technique":"Zero Trust = Trust Nobody, Verify Everything. IAM = who you are, PrivateLink = private path, mTLS = prove it cryptographically.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Zero-trust replaces the traditional perimeter security model (castle-and-moat). Instead of trusting everything inside the network, every connection is authenticated — the same principle behind BeyondCorp and modern ZTNA solutions."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a multi-account AWS landing zone with automated account vending, centralised logging, and guardrails with the least custom development. Which service provides this?","options":["AWS Organizations alone","AWS Control Tower","AWS Service Catalog","Custom Lambda with CloudFormation StackSets"],"correct_answer":"AWS Control Tower","explanation":"AWS Control Tower automates the setup of a multi-account AWS environment based on AWS best practices. It provides account vending via Account Factory, centralised logging to a Log Archive account, and preventive/detective guardrails via SCPs and Config Rules.","memory_technique":"Control Tower = Air Traffic Control for AWS accounts. Manages the landing zone, controls who lands where, and enforces flight rules (guardrails).","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Control Tower replaces custom account provisioning scripts. It's equivalent to an automated IT onboarding system that provisions new business units with pre-configured, compliant environments."},
  {"question_text":"A company runs a multi-tenant SaaS application on AWS. They need to isolate each tenant's data in DynamoDB while using a single table. Which approach provides the strongest isolation with the least operational overhead?","options":["Separate DynamoDB tables per tenant","Partition key prefix per tenant with IAM condition keys (dynamodb:LeadingKeys) to restrict access","Separate AWS accounts per tenant","Encrypt each tenant's data with a different KMS key"],"correct_answer":"Partition key prefix per tenant with IAM condition keys (dynamodb:LeadingKeys) to restrict access","explanation":"Using tenant ID as a partition key prefix combined with IAM condition key dynamodb:LeadingKeys restricts each tenant's IAM role to only access items where the partition key starts with their tenant ID. This provides strong logical isolation in a single table without the operational overhead of managing separate tables or accounts.","memory_technique":"LeadingKeys = Leading the way to your data only. Your IAM policy says 'you can only touch rows that start with YOUR tenant ID'.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"This is the cloud equivalent of row-level security in relational databases (Oracle VPD, PostgreSQL RLS). The IAM condition key enforces tenant isolation at the API level."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a data lake on AWS that automatically catalogs data, enforces access controls at the column level, and enables cross-account data sharing. Which service provides these capabilities?","options":["Amazon S3 with bucket policies","AWS Glue Data Catalog","AWS Lake Formation","Amazon Redshift Spectrum"],"correct_answer":"AWS Lake Formation","explanation":"AWS Lake Formation simplifies building, securing, and managing data lakes. It provides centralised access control including column-level security, row-level filtering, and cross-account data sharing through AWS RAM.","memory_technique":"Lake Formation = Lake Warden. Manages who can fish in which part of the lake, down to which type of fish (column-level security).","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Lake Formation replaces complex combinations of S3 policies, Glue catalog permissions, and Athena workgroups. It provides the centralised data governance that traditional data warehouses had built-in."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between AWS CloudFormation StackSets and nested stacks?","options":["They are the same feature","StackSets deploy stacks across multiple accounts and regions; nested stacks are stacks within stacks in a single account","StackSets are for large stacks; nested stacks are for small stacks","Nested stacks deploy across accounts; StackSets are for single-account deployments"],"correct_answer":"StackSets deploy stacks across multiple accounts and regions; nested stacks are stacks within stacks in a single account","explanation":"CloudFormation StackSets extend the functionality of stacks by enabling you to create, update, or delete stacks across multiple accounts and regions with a single operation. Nested stacks allow you to create modular, reusable templates by referencing other stacks within a parent stack.","memory_technique":"StackSets = Multi-account deployment (horizontal scale). Nested stacks = Modular templates (vertical organisation). StackSets go wide; nested stacks go deep.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"StackSets are equivalent to deploying configuration changes across multiple data centers simultaneously. Nested stacks are equivalent to modular infrastructure templates that reference shared components."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement event-driven architecture where multiple downstream services react to order placement events. Which AWS pattern is most appropriate?","options":["Direct API calls from the order service to each downstream service","Amazon SNS topic with multiple SQS queue subscribers (fan-out pattern)","A single SQS queue shared by all downstream services","AWS Step Functions orchestrating all downstream services"],"correct_answer":"Amazon SNS topic with multiple SQS queue subscribers (fan-out pattern)","explanation":"The SNS fan-out pattern publishes a message to an SNS topic, which delivers it to multiple SQS queues simultaneously. Each downstream service has its own SQS queue, providing independent processing, retry logic, and failure isolation.","memory_technique":"Fan-out = One message, many queues. SNS shouts the order; each service's SQS queue catches its own copy. Independent processing, no coupling.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"The SNS fan-out pattern replaces point-to-point integrations between services. It's equivalent to a publish-subscribe event bus in enterprise integration patterns (EIP) — one event triggers multiple independent consumers."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Well-Architected Framework recommendation for handling failures in distributed systems?","options":["Prevent all failures through redundancy","Design for failure — assume components will fail and build systems that continue to operate despite failures","Use a single large instance to avoid distributed system complexity","Rely on AWS SLAs to prevent failures"],"correct_answer":"Design for failure — assume components will fail and build systems that continue to operate despite failures","explanation":"AWS recommends designing for failure — assuming that any component can fail at any time and building systems that continue to operate despite those failures. This includes using multiple AZs, health checks, auto-scaling, and circuit breakers.","memory_technique":"Design for failure = Expect the worst, build for it. Like designing a building to withstand earthquakes — not hoping they won't happen.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"This is the cloud-native application of the traditional IT principle of fault tolerance — designing systems with redundancy and graceful degradation rather than trying to prevent all failures."},
  {"question_text":"A company wants to optimise costs for a workload that runs for 6 hours every night. Which EC2 pricing option is most cost-effective?","options":["On-Demand Instances","Reserved Instances (1-year, All Upfront)","Spot Instances","Dedicated Hosts"],"correct_answer":"Spot Instances","explanation":"For a batch workload that runs 6 hours per night (approximately 25% of the time) and can tolerate interruption, Spot Instances provide up to 90% discount over On-Demand. Reserved Instances would be wasteful since the workload only runs 25% of the time.","memory_technique":"Batch + interruptible + low utilisation = Spot. Reserved is only worth it for 24/7 workloads. Spot wins for batch jobs.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"This mirrors the decision to use spot/preemptible instances for batch processing — a well-established pattern in HPC and data processing where jobs can checkpoint and restart."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Pricing model for data transfer between AWS Regions?","options":["Always free","Charged for data transferred out of a Region; the receiving Region does not charge for ingress","Charged for both sending and receiving Regions","Free for the first 1GB per month, then charged"],"correct_answer":"Charged for data transferred out of a Region; the receiving Region does not charge for ingress","explanation":"Cross-Region data transfer is charged for the data transferred out of the source Region. The destination Region does not charge for ingress. Rates vary by Region pair.","memory_technique":"Cross-Region = Toll road. You pay the toll leaving the source Region. The destination Region welcomes you for free.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Cross-Region transfer pricing mirrors WAN bandwidth costs in traditional IT — you pay for the bandwidth consumed sending data between locations, not for receiving it."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a serverless event-driven architecture that processes S3 uploads, transforms the data, and stores results in DynamoDB. Which combination of services achieves this with the least operational overhead?","options":["EC2 instances polling S3 → RDS","S3 Event Notifications → Lambda → DynamoDB","Kinesis Data Streams → EC2 → RDS","SQS → EC2 → S3"],"correct_answer":"S3 Event Notifications → Lambda → DynamoDB","explanation":"S3 Event Notifications trigger Lambda functions automatically when objects are uploaded. Lambda processes the data and writes to DynamoDB. This is fully serverless — no servers to manage, automatic scaling, and pay-per-use pricing.","memory_technique":"S3 upload → Lambda wakes up → processes → writes to DynamoDB. Fully serverless chain — no servers, no idle costs.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"This serverless pattern replaces traditional ETL pipelines running on always-on servers. It's equivalent to a file watcher script that triggers processing, but fully managed and infinitely scalable."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between Amazon Cognito User Pools and Identity Pools?","options":["They are the same service","User Pools provide user authentication and directory; Identity Pools provide temporary AWS credentials for authenticated users","User Pools are for mobile apps; Identity Pools are for web apps","Identity Pools provide user authentication; User Pools provide AWS credentials"],"correct_answer":"User Pools provide user authentication and directory; Identity Pools provide temporary AWS credentials for authenticated users","explanation":"Cognito User Pools are user directories that provide sign-up, sign-in, and user management. Identity Pools (Federated Identities) exchange user pool tokens (or other identity provider tokens) for temporary AWS credentials to access AWS services directly.","memory_technique":"User Pool = Who you are (authentication). Identity Pool = What you can do in AWS (authorisation via temporary credentials). Pool of users vs. pool of AWS identities.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"User Pools are equivalent to an LDAP/AD user directory; Identity Pools are equivalent to STS federation — exchanging an identity token for temporary AWS access credentials."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to ensure their Lambda functions can access resources in a private VPC (like RDS) while also accessing the internet. What is the correct architecture?","options":["Deploy Lambda in the VPC with a public subnet","Deploy Lambda in the VPC with a private subnet, and add a NAT Gateway for internet access","Deploy Lambda outside the VPC and use VPC peering","Lambda cannot access both VPC resources and the internet simultaneously"],"correct_answer":"Deploy Lambda in the VPC with a private subnet, and add a NAT Gateway for internet access","explanation":"When Lambda is deployed in a VPC, it loses direct internet access. To access both VPC resources (like RDS in a private subnet) and the internet, you deploy Lambda in a private subnet and route internet traffic through a NAT Gateway in a public subnet.","memory_technique":"Lambda in VPC = loses internet. Add NAT Gateway = gets internet back. Private subnet + NAT = best of both worlds.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"This is the standard private subnet + NAT Gateway pattern used in traditional network design — servers in private subnets access the internet through a NAT device, while remaining unreachable from the internet directly."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Well-Architected Framework's Cost Optimisation pillar's recommendation for right-sizing?","options":["Always use the largest instance type for headroom","Continuously analyse resource utilisation and adjust instance types to match actual workload requirements","Right-size only during initial deployment","Use Reserved Instances for all workloads regardless of utilisation"],"correct_answer":"Continuously analyse resource utilisation and adjust instance types to match actual workload requirements","explanation":"The Cost Optimisation pillar recommends continuously monitoring resource utilisation and right-sizing instances to match actual needs. AWS Compute Optimizer and Cost Explorer provide recommendations for right-sizing based on actual usage patterns.","memory_technique":"Right-sizing = Goldilocks principle. Not too big, not too small — just right. Continuously review and adjust.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Right-sizing is equivalent to traditional IT capacity management — reviewing server utilisation reports and decommissioning or downsizing underutilised servers to reduce costs."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a blue/green deployment for their application on AWS to minimise downtime during releases. Which combination of services enables this?","options":["EC2 with manual instance replacement","Elastic Load Balancer with two Auto Scaling Groups (blue and green)","AWS CodeDeploy with in-place deployment","AWS Lambda with versioning only"],"correct_answer":"Elastic Load Balancer with two Auto Scaling Groups (blue and green)","explanation":"Blue/green deployment uses two identical environments. The ELB routes traffic to the blue (current) environment. After deploying to green (new), you shift traffic from blue to green via the ELB. If issues arise, you instantly roll back by shifting traffic back to blue.","memory_technique":"Blue/Green = Two lanes on a highway. Traffic flows in blue lane; you build the green lane, then flip the switch. Instant rollback = flip back.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Blue/green deployment is a standard release engineering pattern. Traditionally it required duplicate hardware; AWS makes it cost-effective by spinning up the green environment only during deployment."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Pricing model for Amazon EKS?","options":["Free — you only pay for the EC2 instances or Fargate","$0.10 per hour per EKS cluster, plus the cost of EC2 instances or Fargate for worker nodes","Fixed monthly fee per cluster","Pay per pod running in the cluster"],"correct_answer":"$0.10 per hour per EKS cluster, plus the cost of EC2 instances or Fargate for worker nodes","explanation":"Amazon EKS charges $0.10 per hour for each EKS cluster (approximately $72/month). You also pay for the EC2 instances or Fargate resources used as worker nodes. There is no charge for the Kubernetes control plane beyond the cluster fee.","memory_technique":"EKS = $0.10/hour for the control plane + EC2/Fargate for workers. The control plane is cheap; the workers are where the real cost is.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"EKS pricing mirrors managed Kubernetes services — you pay a management fee for the control plane and separately for the compute resources running your workloads."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement cross-account access so that a Lambda function in Account A can read from an S3 bucket in Account B. What is the correct approach?","options":["Create an IAM user in Account B and store credentials in Account A's Lambda environment variables","Add a bucket policy in Account B granting access to Account A's Lambda execution role, and ensure the Lambda role has permission to access Account B's S3","Use VPC peering between the two accounts","Enable S3 public access on the bucket in Account B"],"correct_answer":"Add a bucket policy in Account B granting access to Account A's Lambda execution role, and ensure the Lambda role has permission to access Account B's S3","explanation":"Cross-account S3 access requires both a resource-based policy (bucket policy in Account B granting the principal from Account A) and an identity-based policy (IAM policy in Account A allowing the Lambda role to access Account B's S3). Both sides must grant permission.","memory_technique":"Cross-account = Two-door lock. Both doors must be unlocked: resource policy (Account B's door) AND identity policy (Account A's door).","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Cross-account access mirrors inter-domain trust relationships in Active Directory. Both the trusting domain (resource) and the trusted domain (identity) must explicitly allow the access."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Pricing model for Amazon CloudWatch?","options":["Completely free for all features","Free tier includes basic metrics; charges apply for custom metrics, detailed monitoring, logs ingestion, and dashboards","Fixed monthly fee","Pay per alarm only"],"correct_answer":"Free tier includes basic metrics; charges apply for custom metrics, detailed monitoring, logs ingestion, and dashboards","explanation":"CloudWatch has a free tier that includes basic EC2 metrics (5-minute intervals), 10 custom metrics, 10 alarms, and 5GB of log data ingestion. Charges apply for additional custom metrics, detailed monitoring (1-minute intervals), log ingestion beyond the free tier, and dashboards.","memory_technique":"CloudWatch = Free basics, pay for extras. Basic metrics free; custom metrics, detailed monitoring, and logs cost money.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"CloudWatch pricing mirrors traditional monitoring tool licensing — basic infrastructure monitoring is included, but advanced features (custom metrics, log analytics, dashboards) require additional investment."},
]

