questions += [
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between Amazon S3 Glacier and S3 Glacier Deep Archive?","options":["They are the same","Glacier has retrieval times of minutes to hours; Glacier Deep Archive has retrieval times of 12-48 hours but lower cost","Glacier is for databases; Deep Archive is for files","Glacier Deep Archive is faster than Glacier"],"correct_answer":"Glacier has retrieval times of minutes to hours; Glacier Deep Archive has retrieval times of 12-48 hours but lower cost","explanation":"S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval offers retrieval times of minutes to hours. S3 Glacier Deep Archive is the lowest-cost storage class with retrieval times of 12-48 hours, designed for data accessed once or twice per year.","memory_technique":"Deep Archive = Deepest freeze. Cheapest storage, longest thaw time (12-48 hours). For data you almost never need.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Glacier Deep Archive is equivalent to deep cold storage tape archives — the cheapest possible storage for compliance data that must be retained but is rarely accessed."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon SageMaker?","options":["A managed database service","A fully managed machine learning platform for building, training, and deploying ML models","A data warehouse service","A business intelligence service"],"correct_answer":"A fully managed machine learning platform for building, training, and deploying ML models","explanation":"Amazon SageMaker is a fully managed ML platform that provides every developer and data scientist with the ability to build, train, and deploy machine learning models quickly.","memory_technique":"SageMaker = Sage (wise) + Maker. Makes you wise by building ML models. End-to-end ML platform.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"SageMaker replaces custom ML infrastructure (GPU servers, Jupyter notebooks, model serving). It provides the full ML lifecycle in a managed platform."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS CodeBuild?","options":["A code repository service","A fully managed continuous integration service that compiles source code, runs tests, and produces deployable packages","A code review service","A deployment service"],"correct_answer":"A fully managed continuous integration service that compiles source code, runs tests, and produces deployable packages","explanation":"AWS CodeBuild is a fully managed CI service that compiles source code, runs tests, and produces software packages ready for deployment. It scales automatically and charges per build minute.","memory_technique":"CodeBuild = Build your code. CI service that compiles, tests, and packages — the build step in your CI/CD pipeline.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"CodeBuild replaces self-managed Jenkins build servers. It provides the same CI capabilities without managing build infrastructure."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS CodeDeploy?","options":["A code repository service","A fully managed deployment service that automates software deployments to EC2, Lambda, and on-premises servers","A CI service","A code review service"],"correct_answer":"A fully managed deployment service that automates software deployments to EC2, Lambda, and on-premises servers","explanation":"AWS CodeDeploy automates software deployments to a variety of compute services including EC2, Fargate, Lambda, and on-premises servers. It supports rolling, blue/green, and canary deployment strategies.","memory_technique":"CodeDeploy = Deploy your code. Automates the deployment step — rolling updates, blue/green, canary.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"CodeDeploy replaces manual deployment scripts and tools like Capistrano or Fabric. It provides automated, consistent deployments with rollback capabilities."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS CodeCommit?","options":["A CI/CD pipeline service","A fully managed source control service hosting private Git repositories","A code review service","A deployment service"],"correct_answer":"A fully managed source control service hosting private Git repositories","explanation":"AWS CodeCommit is a fully managed source control service that hosts secure Git-based repositories. It integrates with other AWS services and supports standard Git commands.","memory_technique":"CodeCommit = Commit your code. Managed Git hosting — like GitHub but in AWS.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"CodeCommit replaces self-hosted Git servers (GitLab, Bitbucket Server). It provides managed Git hosting with AWS IAM integration for access control."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon QuickSight?","options":["A database service","A fast, cloud-powered business intelligence service for creating visualisations and dashboards","A monitoring service","A data pipeline service"],"correct_answer":"A fast, cloud-powered business intelligence service for creating visualisations and dashboards","explanation":"Amazon QuickSight is a cloud-powered BI service that makes it easy to create and publish interactive dashboards. It connects to various data sources including S3, RDS, Redshift, and Athena.","memory_technique":"QuickSight = Quick insights. BI dashboards that connect to your AWS data sources — like Tableau but managed by AWS.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"QuickSight replaces traditional BI tools like Tableau, Power BI, or Cognos. It provides the same visualisation capabilities as a fully managed AWS service."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between AWS CloudFormation and AWS Elastic Beanstalk?","options":["They are the same service","CloudFormation is infrastructure as code for any AWS resource; Elastic Beanstalk is a PaaS for deploying web applications","CloudFormation is for EC2 only; Elastic Beanstalk is for all services","Elastic Beanstalk uses CloudFormation under the hood but they serve different purposes"],"correct_answer":"Elastic Beanstalk is a PaaS for deploying web applications","explanation":"CloudFormation is a general-purpose IaC service for provisioning any AWS resource. Elastic Beanstalk is a PaaS specifically for deploying web applications — it uses CloudFormation under the hood but abstracts the infrastructure details.","memory_technique":"CloudFormation = Full control (you define everything). Beanstalk = Opinionated PaaS (AWS decides the infrastructure). Beanstalk is built on CloudFormation.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"CloudFormation is like Terraform — full infrastructure control. Beanstalk is like Heroku — opinionated PaaS where you just push code."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon EventBridge?","options":["A network bridge service","A serverless event bus that connects applications using events from AWS services, SaaS applications, and custom sources","A message queue service","A workflow orchestration service"],"correct_answer":"A serverless event bus that connects applications using events from AWS services, SaaS applications, and custom sources","explanation":"Amazon EventBridge is a serverless event bus that makes it easy to connect applications using events. It receives events from AWS services, SaaS applications, and custom applications, and routes them to targets.","memory_technique":"EventBridge = Event highway. Events flow from sources to targets — like a smart switchboard for events.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"EventBridge replaces custom event routing logic and integrates with SaaS event sources. It's equivalent to an enterprise service bus (ESB) but serverless and event-driven."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS X-Ray?","options":["A security scanning service","A distributed tracing service that helps analyse and debug distributed applications","A network monitoring service","A log analysis service"],"correct_answer":"A distributed tracing service that helps analyse and debug distributed applications","explanation":"AWS X-Ray helps developers analyse and debug distributed applications in production. It provides an end-to-end view of requests as they travel through your application, identifying performance bottlenecks and errors.","memory_technique":"X-Ray = See through your application. Traces requests through all your microservices — like an X-ray showing the skeleton of your app.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"X-Ray replaces custom distributed tracing implementations and third-party APM tools like Jaeger or Zipkin. It provides the same distributed tracing capabilities integrated with AWS services."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon Forecast?","options":["A weather forecasting service","A fully managed service that uses ML to deliver highly accurate time-series forecasts","A cost forecasting service","A capacity planning service"],"correct_answer":"A fully managed service that uses ML to deliver highly accurate time-series forecasts","explanation":"Amazon Forecast is a fully managed service that uses machine learning to deliver highly accurate forecasts. It is based on the same technology used at Amazon.com for demand forecasting.","memory_technique":"Forecast = Predict the future. ML-powered time-series forecasting — like a crystal ball for your data.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Amazon Forecast replaces custom time-series forecasting models and statistical tools like R or Python statsmodels. It provides ML-based forecasting without requiring data science expertise."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between Amazon CloudWatch Logs and Amazon CloudWatch Metrics?","options":["They are the same","CloudWatch Logs stores and analyses log data; CloudWatch Metrics stores numerical time-series data","CloudWatch Logs is for applications; CloudWatch Metrics is for infrastructure only","CloudWatch Metrics stores logs; CloudWatch Logs stores metrics"],"correct_answer":"CloudWatch Logs stores and analyses log data; CloudWatch Metrics stores numerical time-series data","explanation":"CloudWatch Logs is a log management service for storing, monitoring, and analysing log files. CloudWatch Metrics stores numerical time-series data (CPU utilisation, request count) that can be graphed and alarmed on.","memory_technique":"Logs = Text records (what happened). Metrics = Numbers over time (how much/how fast). Logs tell stories; metrics tell numbers.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"CloudWatch Logs is equivalent to a centralised log management system (ELK Stack, Splunk). CloudWatch Metrics is equivalent to a time-series monitoring system (Prometheus, Graphite)."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Trusted Advisor's Cost Optimisation category?","options":["Checks for security vulnerabilities","Identifies idle and underutilised resources, Reserved Instance optimisation opportunities, and other cost savings","Checks for performance bottlenecks","Checks for service limit violations"],"correct_answer":"Identifies idle and underutilised resources, Reserved Instance optimisation opportunities, and other cost savings","explanation":"Trusted Advisor's Cost Optimisation checks identify opportunities to reduce costs, including idle EC2 instances, underutilised EBS volumes, unassociated Elastic IP addresses, and Reserved Instance purchase recommendations.","memory_technique":"Cost Optimisation = Find the waste. Trusted Advisor finds idle resources and unused reservations — like a financial auditor finding unnecessary expenses.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"Trusted Advisor's cost checks are equivalent to a cloud cost optimisation review — identifying waste and recommending right-sizing, similar to what FinOps consultants do manually."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Pricing model for Amazon ECS?","options":["Pay per container","Free for ECS itself; you pay for the underlying EC2 instances or Fargate resources","Fixed monthly fee per cluster","Pay per task definition"],"correct_answer":"Free for ECS itself; you pay for the underlying EC2 instances or Fargate resources","explanation":"There is no additional charge for Amazon ECS. You pay for the AWS resources (EC2 instances or Fargate) you create to store and run your application. ECS itself is free.","memory_technique":"ECS = Free orchestration. You pay for the compute (EC2 or Fargate), not the orchestrator. Like a free conductor — you pay the musicians.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":3,"it_context_mapping":"ECS pricing mirrors the model of free open-source orchestration tools — the orchestration layer is free, you pay for the underlying compute resources."},
]

