# ADDITIONAL QUESTIONS — Difficulty 4 & 5 (more coverage)
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
questions += [
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of Amazon S3 Object Lock?","options":["To prevent objects from being read","To store objects using a write-once-read-many (WORM) model, preventing deletion or overwriting for a specified period","To lock S3 bucket permissions","To prevent S3 bucket deletion"],"correct_answer":"To store objects using a write-once-read-many (WORM) model, preventing deletion or overwriting for a specified period","explanation":"S3 Object Lock stores objects using a WORM model. It can prevent objects from being deleted or overwritten for a fixed amount of time or indefinitely, supporting compliance requirements like SEC Rule 17a-4.","memory_technique":"Object Lock = Write Once, Read Many. Like carving in stone — once written, cannot be changed or deleted.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"S3 Object Lock replaces WORM storage appliances (like NetApp SnapLock or EMC Centera) used for regulatory compliance. It provides the same immutability guarantees for compliance data."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon Macie's primary use case?","options":["Detecting network intrusions","Automatically discovering and protecting sensitive data (PII, financial data) stored in S3","Scanning EC2 instances for vulnerabilities","Monitoring API calls for suspicious activity"],"correct_answer":"Automatically discovering and protecting sensitive data (PII, financial data) stored in S3","explanation":"Amazon Macie uses machine learning to automatically discover, classify, and protect sensitive data in S3. It identifies PII (names, addresses, credit card numbers) and alerts on policy violations or unusual access patterns.","memory_technique":"Macie = Data Detective. Finds hidden sensitive data in your S3 buckets using ML.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Macie replaces traditional DLP (Data Loss Prevention) tools. It provides automated sensitive data discovery without manually defining patterns for every type of sensitive data."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between AWS Config and AWS CloudTrail?","options":["They are the same service","CloudTrail records API calls (who did what); AWS Config records resource configurations (what changed)","CloudTrail records configurations; Config records API calls","Config is for billing; CloudTrail is for security"],"correct_answer":"CloudTrail records API calls (who did what); AWS Config records resource configurations (what changed)","explanation":"CloudTrail answers 'who made this API call?' Config answers 'what does this resource look like now, and how has it changed over time?' They complement each other for security and compliance.","memory_technique":"CloudTrail = Activity log (who did what). Config = Configuration history (what changed). Trail = actions; Config = state.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"CloudTrail is like an audit log (who logged in, what commands ran). Config is like a CMDB with change history (what the server configuration looks like and how it changed)."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of AWS GuardDuty threat intelligence feeds?","options":["To provide weather data for AWS regions","To enhance threat detection with known malicious IP addresses, domains, and file hashes","To provide pricing intelligence","To provide performance benchmarks"],"correct_answer":"To enhance threat detection with known malicious IP addresses, domains, and file hashes","explanation":"GuardDuty uses threat intelligence feeds from AWS Security and third-party providers (like CrowdStrike and Proofpoint) containing known malicious IP addresses, domains, and file hashes to enhance its threat detection capabilities.","memory_technique":"Threat intelligence = Known bad guys list. GuardDuty checks your traffic against this list to spot known threats.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Threat intelligence feeds are equivalent to IP reputation databases used in traditional firewalls and IDS/IPS systems — blocking or alerting on traffic from known malicious sources."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Well-Architected Framework's Security pillar's recommendation for identity management?","options":["Use a single shared admin account for all operations","Implement strong identity foundation with least privilege, MFA, and centralised identity management","Allow all users full access for productivity","Use only root account credentials for simplicity"],"correct_answer":"Implement strong identity foundation with least privilege, MFA, and centralised identity management","explanation":"The Security pillar recommends implementing a strong identity foundation: use least privilege, enforce MFA, centralise identity management, and eliminate long-term static credentials where possible.","memory_technique":"Security pillar identity = Least privilege + MFA + centralised. The three pillars of identity security.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"This maps to traditional IAM best practices: RBAC (least privilege), two-factor authentication (MFA), and centralised directory services (Active Directory)."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon Detective used for in a security investigation?","options":["Preventing security incidents","Analysing and visualising security data to investigate the root cause and scope of security findings","Scanning for vulnerabilities","Blocking malicious traffic"],"correct_answer":"Analysing and visualising security data to investigate the root cause and scope of security findings","explanation":"Amazon Detective automatically collects log data and uses ML to create interactive visualisations for security investigations. When GuardDuty identifies a threat, Detective helps you understand what happened, who was involved, and what resources were affected.","memory_technique":"Detective = Post-incident investigator. GuardDuty finds the crime; Detective investigates the crime scene.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Amazon Detective is equivalent to a SIEM's investigation and forensics module — correlating events across multiple data sources to understand the full scope of a security incident."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of AWS Audit Manager?","options":["To audit EC2 instance performance","To continuously audit AWS usage to simplify risk assessment and compliance with regulations","To audit IAM policies","To audit network traffic"],"correct_answer":"To continuously audit AWS usage to simplify risk assessment and compliance with regulations","explanation":"AWS Audit Manager helps you continuously audit your AWS usage to simplify how you assess risk and compliance with regulations and industry standards like PCI DSS, HIPAA, and GDPR.","memory_technique":"Audit Manager = Compliance autopilot. Continuously collects evidence for audits — no more scrambling before an audit.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Audit Manager replaces manual evidence collection for compliance audits. It's equivalent to a GRC (Governance, Risk, Compliance) tool that automatically collects and organises audit evidence."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between Amazon EBS gp2 and gp3 volumes?","options":["They are identical","gp3 allows you to independently provision IOPS and throughput separate from storage size, while gp2 ties IOPS to storage size","gp2 is faster than gp3","gp3 is only for databases"],"correct_answer":"gp3 allows you to independently provision IOPS and throughput separate from storage size, while gp2 ties IOPS to storage size","explanation":"gp2 volumes provide 3 IOPS per GB (up to 16,000 IOPS) tied to volume size. gp3 volumes allow you to independently provision up to 16,000 IOPS and 1,000 MB/s throughput regardless of volume size, and are 20% cheaper than gp2.","memory_technique":"gp3 = Flexible performance. Provision IOPS and throughput independently from size. gp2 = IOPS tied to size (3 IOPS/GB).","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"gp3 is equivalent to a storage system where you can independently configure IOPS and capacity — like enterprise SAN storage where performance and capacity are separate dimensions."},
  {"question_text":"What is Amazon S3 Transfer Acceleration?","options":["A service that accelerates S3 object replication","A feature that enables fast, easy, and secure transfers of files over long distances using CloudFront edge locations","A service that accelerates S3 encryption","A feature that speeds up S3 bucket creation"],"correct_answer":"A feature that enables fast, easy, and secure transfers of files over long distances using CloudFront edge locations","explanation":"S3 Transfer Acceleration enables fast transfers of files to and from S3 by routing data through CloudFront's globally distributed edge locations. It is particularly useful for uploading large files from distant locations.","memory_technique":"Transfer Acceleration = Express lane for S3 uploads. Data enters the AWS network at the nearest edge location instead of travelling the full internet distance.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"S3 Transfer Acceleration is equivalent to using a CDN's upload acceleration feature — routing uploads through the nearest PoP to reduce latency for geographically distant users."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of Amazon VPC Peering?","options":["To connect a VPC to the internet","To connect two VPCs privately using AWS's network infrastructure","To connect a VPC to on-premises","To connect a VPC to AWS services"],"correct_answer":"To connect two VPCs privately using AWS's network infrastructure","explanation":"VPC Peering creates a networking connection between two VPCs that enables routing traffic between them using private IP addresses. Peered VPCs can be in the same account, different accounts, or different regions.","memory_technique":"VPC Peering = Private handshake between VPCs. Two VPCs become peers — they can talk to each other privately.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"VPC Peering is equivalent to a private network interconnect between two data centers — traffic stays on the private network without traversing the internet."},
  {"question_text":"What is AWS Wavelength?","options":["A network monitoring service","A service that embeds AWS compute and storage within telecommunications providers' 5G networks for ultra-low latency applications","A satellite connectivity service","A wireless networking service"],"correct_answer":"A service that embeds AWS compute and storage within telecommunications providers' 5G networks for ultra-low latency applications","explanation":"AWS Wavelength embeds AWS compute and storage services within communications service providers' data centers at the edge of the 5G network. This minimises latency for applications that require single-digit millisecond latency.","memory_technique":"Wavelength = AWS at the 5G edge. Compute runs inside the telecom network — milliseconds from mobile devices.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Wavelength is equivalent to mobile edge computing (MEC) — running compute at the base station level to minimise latency for mobile applications like AR/VR, autonomous vehicles, and real-time gaming."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of Amazon S3 Replication?","options":["To replicate S3 buckets within the same region only","To automatically replicate objects between S3 buckets, either within the same region (SRR) or across regions (CRR)","To replicate S3 data to EBS","To replicate S3 data to on-premises storage"],"correct_answer":"To automatically replicate objects between S3 buckets, either within the same region (SRR) or across regions (CRR)","explanation":"S3 Replication automatically replicates objects between buckets. Same-Region Replication (SRR) replicates within the same region for compliance or aggregation. Cross-Region Replication (CRR) replicates across regions for DR or latency reduction.","memory_technique":"SRR = Same Region Replication (compliance, aggregation). CRR = Cross-Region Replication (DR, global access). Both are automatic.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"S3 Replication is equivalent to storage array replication (synchronous or asynchronous) between data centers — automatically keeping copies of data in multiple locations."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Pricing model for Amazon EBS?","options":["Pay per I/O operation only","Pay per GB-month of provisioned storage, plus IOPS for io1/io2 volumes, plus snapshot storage","Fixed monthly fee","Pay per read/write operation"],"correct_answer":"Pay per GB-month of provisioned storage, plus IOPS for io1/io2 volumes, plus snapshot storage","explanation":"EBS pricing includes: provisioned storage (per GB-month, varying by volume type), provisioned IOPS for io1/io2 volumes (per IOPS-month), and snapshot storage (per GB-month). gp3 volumes allow separate IOPS provisioning.","memory_technique":"EBS = Pay for what you provision, not what you use. Storage + IOPS (for io volumes) + snapshots.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"EBS pricing mirrors SAN storage pricing — you pay for provisioned capacity and IOPS, not actual utilisation. This is why right-sizing EBS volumes is important for cost optimisation."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Pricing model for Amazon ElastiCache?","options":["Pay per cache hit","Pay per node-hour based on node type, plus data transfer","Fixed monthly fee","Pay per GB of cached data"],"correct_answer":"Pay per node-hour based on node type, plus data transfer","explanation":"ElastiCache pricing is based on the node type and number of nodes (per node-hour), plus data transfer. Reserved nodes are available for significant discounts on predictable workloads.","memory_technique":"ElastiCache = Pay per node per hour. Like EC2 pricing but for cache nodes.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"ElastiCache pricing mirrors the cost of running Redis or Memcached on EC2 — you pay for the compute resources, but AWS manages the cache software and infrastructure."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Pricing model for AWS Lambda@Edge?","options":["Same as regular Lambda","Lambda@Edge charges are higher than regular Lambda — based on requests and duration at edge locations","Lambda@Edge is free","Lambda@Edge uses CloudFront pricing only"],"correct_answer":"Lambda@Edge charges are higher than regular Lambda — based on requests and duration at edge locations","explanation":"Lambda@Edge pricing is based on the number of requests and the duration of function execution at CloudFront edge locations. The rates are higher than regular Lambda because functions run at edge locations globally.","memory_technique":"Lambda@Edge = Lambda at the edge (more expensive). You pay a premium for running code close to users at CloudFront edge locations.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":4,"it_context_mapping":"Lambda@Edge pricing reflects the premium for edge computing — running code at distributed edge locations costs more than centralised cloud compute, similar to CDN pricing premiums."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a canary deployment for their Lambda function. Which feature enables this?","options":["Lambda layers","Lambda aliases with traffic shifting","Lambda versions only","Lambda environment variables"],"correct_answer":"Lambda aliases with traffic shifting","explanation":"Lambda aliases support traffic shifting, allowing you to route a percentage of traffic to a new version (canary) while keeping most traffic on the stable version. You can gradually shift traffic and roll back instantly if issues arise.","memory_technique":"Lambda alias + traffic shifting = Canary deployment. Send 5% to the new version, watch for errors, then shift 100%.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Lambda canary deployments mirror traditional canary releases — gradually rolling out changes to a small percentage of users before full deployment, reducing risk."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of Amazon S3 Intelligent-Tiering Archive configurations?","options":["To archive all S3 data automatically","To automatically move objects to Glacier tiers after a configurable number of days without access, extending cost savings beyond the standard tiers","To archive S3 metadata","To archive S3 access logs"],"correct_answer":"To automatically move objects to Glacier tiers after a configurable number of days without access, extending cost savings beyond the standard tiers","explanation":"S3 Intelligent-Tiering can be configured with optional archive tiers (Archive Access and Deep Archive Access) that automatically move objects to Glacier tiers after 90 or 180 days without access, providing additional cost savings for rarely accessed data.","memory_technique":"Intelligent-Tiering Archive = Smart deep freeze. Automatically moves cold data to Glacier tiers — maximum automation, maximum savings.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"This is equivalent to automated storage tiering with deep archive — automatically moving data through hot, warm, and cold tiers based on access patterns, maximising cost efficiency."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Pricing model for Amazon Redshift Serverless?","options":["Fixed monthly fee","Pay per Redshift Processing Unit (RPU) per second for compute, plus storage","Pay per query","Pay per user"],"correct_answer":"Pay per Redshift Processing Unit (RPU) per second for compute, plus storage","explanation":"Amazon Redshift Serverless charges based on Redshift Processing Units (RPUs) consumed per second during query execution, plus storage costs. You only pay when queries are running — no idle costs.","memory_technique":"Redshift Serverless = Pay per query second. RPUs consumed × seconds running = your cost. Zero idle cost.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Redshift Serverless pricing mirrors serverless database pricing — you pay for actual query execution time rather than provisioned capacity, similar to Athena's per-query pricing model."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between AWS Direct Connect and AWS VPN?","options":["They are the same","Direct Connect provides a dedicated private connection with consistent performance; VPN provides an encrypted connection over the public internet","Direct Connect is encrypted; VPN is not","VPN provides dedicated bandwidth; Direct Connect uses shared bandwidth"],"correct_answer":"Direct Connect provides a dedicated private connection with consistent performance; VPN provides an encrypted connection over the public internet","explanation":"Direct Connect provides a dedicated private network connection with consistent bandwidth and latency, bypassing the public internet. VPN provides an encrypted tunnel over the public internet — lower cost but variable performance.","memory_technique":"Direct Connect = Private highway (dedicated, consistent). VPN = Encrypted public road (cheaper, variable). Choose based on performance requirements and budget.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Direct Connect is like a leased line; VPN is like an encrypted internet connection. Traditional enterprises use leased lines for critical connections and VPN for backup or less critical links."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of Amazon S3 Batch Operations?","options":["To process S3 objects in real time","To perform large-scale batch operations on billions of S3 objects with a single request","To batch upload files to S3","To batch delete S3 buckets"],"correct_answer":"To perform large-scale batch operations on billions of S3 objects with a single request","explanation":"S3 Batch Operations allows you to perform large-scale batch operations on S3 objects — such as copying objects, invoking Lambda functions, restoring from Glacier, or setting tags — across billions of objects with a single API call.","memory_technique":"S3 Batch Operations = Bulk action on S3. One job to process billions of objects — like a bulk find-and-replace for your entire S3 estate.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"S3 Batch Operations replaces custom scripts that iterate through S3 objects. It's equivalent to a bulk database update operation — one command affects millions of records."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Pricing model for Amazon Aurora?","options":["Fixed monthly fee","Pay per ACU (Aurora Capacity Unit) for serverless, or per instance-hour for provisioned, plus storage and I/O","Pay per query","Pay per database connection"],"correct_answer":"Pay per ACU (Aurora Capacity Unit) for serverless, or per instance-hour for provisioned, plus storage and I/O","explanation":"Aurora Provisioned charges per instance-hour based on instance type, plus storage (per GB-month) and I/O (per million requests). Aurora Serverless charges per ACU-second for compute, plus storage.","memory_technique":"Aurora = Instance-hour (provisioned) or ACU-second (serverless) + storage + I/O. Serverless scales to zero; provisioned is always running.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Aurora pricing mirrors the choice between reserved and on-demand database capacity — provisioned for predictable workloads, serverless for variable or intermittent workloads."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of AWS Service Quotas?","options":["To set billing limits","To view and manage your quotas (limits) for AWS services from a central location, and request increases","To manage service level agreements","To set performance quotas"],"correct_answer":"To view and manage your quotas (limits) for AWS services from a central location, and request increases","explanation":"AWS Service Quotas provides a central location to view and manage your quotas for AWS services. You can view current quota values, request increases, and set CloudWatch alarms when approaching quota limits.","memory_technique":"Service Quotas = AWS speed limits. View how fast you can go (current limits) and request a higher speed limit (quota increase).","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Service Quotas is equivalent to capacity management in traditional IT — tracking how close you are to infrastructure limits and requesting additional capacity before hitting them."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between Amazon CloudFront and AWS Global Accelerator?","options":["They are the same service","CloudFront is a CDN that caches content at edge locations; Global Accelerator routes traffic through the AWS network for improved performance without caching","CloudFront is for static content only; Global Accelerator is for dynamic content only","Global Accelerator caches content; CloudFront routes traffic"],"correct_answer":"CloudFront is a CDN that caches content at edge locations; Global Accelerator routes traffic through the AWS network for improved performance without caching","explanation":"CloudFront is a CDN that caches content at edge locations to reduce latency for cacheable content. Global Accelerator routes traffic through the AWS global network to improve performance for non-cacheable, dynamic content and provides static IP addresses.","memory_technique":"CloudFront = Cache at the edge (static content). Global Accelerator = Fast lane on AWS network (dynamic content, static IPs). CloudFront caches; Accelerator routes.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"CloudFront is like a CDN for static assets; Global Accelerator is like a private WAN for dynamic traffic. Both improve performance but through different mechanisms."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Pricing model for Amazon Kinesis Data Streams?","options":["Pay per message","Pay per shard-hour plus per million PUT payload units","Fixed monthly fee","Pay per GB of data processed"],"correct_answer":"Pay per shard-hour plus per million PUT payload units","explanation":"Kinesis Data Streams pricing is based on shard-hours (each shard provides 1 MB/s ingestion and 2 MB/s retrieval) and PUT payload units (per million 25KB chunks). You provision shards based on your throughput requirements.","memory_technique":"Kinesis = Pay for shards (capacity) + PUTs (usage). Shards = lanes on the data highway. More lanes = more throughput = more cost.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Kinesis shard pricing mirrors provisioned capacity pricing — you pay for reserved throughput capacity (shards) regardless of actual usage, similar to provisioned IOPS for EBS."},
]
