# BATCH 3 — Difficulty 5 (fill to 100)
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
questions += [
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a multi-account strategy where each team gets their own AWS account but shares a common VPC for networking. Which combination of services achieves this?","options":["VPC Peering between all accounts","AWS RAM to share VPC subnets across accounts in AWS Organizations","Create one large VPC in a single account for all teams","AWS Transit Gateway with separate VPCs per account"],"correct_answer":"AWS RAM to share VPC subnets across accounts in AWS Organizations","explanation":"AWS RAM allows you to share VPC subnets with other accounts in your Organisation. Each team gets their own account (for billing isolation and blast radius reduction) but launches resources into shared subnets, simplifying network management.","memory_technique":"RAM + shared subnets = Shared apartment building. Each team has their own apartment (account) but shares the hallways (subnets).","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"This mirrors the traditional shared services model — a central networking team manages the network infrastructure while application teams deploy into designated network segments."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a serverless data pipeline that processes CSV files uploaded to S3, validates the data, transforms it to Parquet format, and loads it into a data lake. Which architecture is most appropriate?","options":["EC2 instances polling S3","S3 Event → Lambda (validate) → Step Functions → Glue ETL (transform to Parquet) → S3 data lake","Kinesis Data Streams → EC2 → RDS","Manual processing with scripts"],"correct_answer":"S3 Event → Lambda (validate) → Step Functions → Glue ETL (transform to Parquet) → S3 data lake","explanation":"S3 events trigger Lambda for lightweight validation. Step Functions orchestrates the workflow. Glue ETL handles the heavy transformation to Parquet format. The result lands in the S3 data lake. All serverless, no infrastructure to manage.","memory_technique":"S3 → Lambda → Step Functions → Glue → S3. Each service does what it's best at: trigger, validate, orchestrate, transform, store.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"This serverless pipeline replaces traditional ETL servers running Informatica or SSIS. Each component is managed and scales independently."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between AWS Organizations SCPs and IAM Permission Boundaries?","options":["They are the same","SCPs set maximum permissions for entire accounts; Permission Boundaries set maximum permissions for individual IAM entities within an account","SCPs apply to users; Permission Boundaries apply to accounts","Permission Boundaries override SCPs"],"correct_answer":"SCPs set maximum permissions for entire accounts; Permission Boundaries set maximum permissions for individual IAM entities within an account","explanation":"SCPs define the maximum permissions for all principals in an account (account-level guardrails). Permission Boundaries define the maximum permissions for a specific IAM user or role (entity-level guardrails). Both are restrictive — they can only limit, not grant permissions.","memory_technique":"SCP = Account fence (nobody in this account can do X). Permission Boundary = Individual fence (this specific user/role can't do X). Both are ceilings, not floors.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"SCPs are like domain-level GPOs; Permission Boundaries are like per-user privilege restrictions. Both implement the principle of least privilege at different scopes."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a disaster recovery solution for their DynamoDB tables across regions with RPO of zero and automatic failover. Which feature provides this?","options":["DynamoDB Backups with cross-region restore","DynamoDB Global Tables","DynamoDB Streams with Lambda replication","DynamoDB Point-in-Time Recovery"],"correct_answer":"DynamoDB Global Tables","explanation":"DynamoDB Global Tables provide fully managed, multi-region, multi-active replication with RPO of zero (all writes are replicated to all regions within seconds). Failover is automatic — applications can read and write to any region.","memory_technique":"Global Tables = Multi-region, multi-active DynamoDB. Write anywhere, read anywhere, zero RPO. Like having the same table in every region simultaneously.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"DynamoDB Global Tables replace complex multi-master database replication setups. They provide the same active-active multi-region capability that traditionally required expensive Oracle GoldenGate or similar tools."},
  {"question_text":"A company wants to implement infrastructure as code with the ability to detect and remediate configuration drift automatically. Which combination of AWS services achieves this?","options":["CloudFormation only","CloudFormation with drift detection + AWS Config Rules with auto-remediation via SSM Automation","Terraform only","AWS CDK with manual checks"],"correct_answer":"CloudFormation with drift detection + AWS Config Rules with auto-remediation via SSM Automation","explanation":"CloudFormation drift detection identifies when resources have been manually changed. AWS Config Rules continuously evaluate compliance. SSM Automation documents can automatically remediate non-compliant resources — creating a closed-loop system that detects and fixes drift.","memory_technique":"CloudFormation detects drift → Config Rules evaluate compliance → SSM Automation fixes it. Detect → Evaluate → Remediate. Closed loop.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"This closed-loop pattern mirrors enterprise configuration management — Chef/Puppet detect drift and auto-correct, combined with compliance scanning that triggers remediation workflows."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between Amazon Cognito User Pools and AWS IAM Identity Center for application authentication?","options":["They are the same","User Pools are for customer-facing apps (B2C); IAM Identity Center is for workforce identity (B2B/internal)","User Pools are for internal apps; IAM Identity Center is for external apps","IAM Identity Center replaces User Pools entirely"],"correct_answer":"User Pools are for customer-facing apps (B2C); IAM Identity Center is for workforce identity (B2B/internal)","explanation":"Cognito User Pools are designed for customer-facing applications — self-service sign-up, social login, millions of users. IAM Identity Center is for workforce identity — employees accessing AWS accounts and business applications via SSO with corporate credentials.","memory_technique":"Cognito = Customers (B2C, self-service). IAM Identity Center = Employees (B2B, corporate SSO). Different audiences, different tools.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Cognito is like Auth0 or Firebase Auth (customer identity). IAM Identity Center is like Okta or ADFS (workforce identity). Different identity management patterns for different user populations."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a cost allocation strategy that attributes shared infrastructure costs (like Transit Gateway and shared VPCs) proportionally to the teams using them. Which approach is most effective?","options":["Tag all resources with team names","Use AWS Cost Categories with rules based on account, tag, and service to create custom allocation logic","Use Consolidated Billing only","Manually calculate and invoice each team"],"correct_answer":"Use AWS Cost Categories with rules based on account, tag, and service to create custom allocation logic","explanation":"AWS Cost Categories allow you to create custom rules that map costs to business categories. You can combine account-based, tag-based, and service-based rules to proportionally allocate shared infrastructure costs to consuming teams.","memory_technique":"Cost Categories = Custom cost allocation rules. Define rules like 'Transit Gateway costs split 40/30/30 between teams A/B/C based on traffic proportion.'","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Cost Categories mirror enterprise IT chargeback models — allocating shared infrastructure costs (network, storage, facilities) proportionally to consuming business units based on usage metrics."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of AWS Compute Optimizer's EC2 instance type recommendations?","options":["To recommend the cheapest instance regardless of performance","To analyse CPU, memory, and network utilisation and recommend optimal instance types that balance performance and cost","To recommend Reserved Instance purchases","To recommend Spot Instance usage"],"correct_answer":"To analyse CPU, memory, and network utilisation and recommend optimal instance types that balance performance and cost","explanation":"Compute Optimizer analyses 14 days of CloudWatch metrics (CPU, memory, network, disk) and uses ML to recommend optimal EC2 instance types. It identifies over-provisioned instances (wasting money) and under-provisioned instances (risking performance).","memory_technique":"Compute Optimizer = Right-sizing advisor. Analyses your actual usage and says 'you're using a truck to carry a sandwich — try a sedan instead.'","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Compute Optimizer is equivalent to capacity management tools that analyse server utilisation and recommend right-sizing — replacing manual analysis of CPU/memory metrics."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a solution where developers can provision pre-approved infrastructure without direct AWS console access. Which service provides this self-service capability with governance?","options":["AWS CloudFormation directly","AWS Service Catalog with launch constraints","AWS CDK","AWS Elastic Beanstalk"],"correct_answer":"AWS Service Catalog with launch constraints","explanation":"AWS Service Catalog allows administrators to create portfolios of approved CloudFormation products. Developers can launch these products through a self-service portal without needing direct AWS console access. Launch constraints ensure resources are created with appropriate IAM roles.","memory_technique":"Service Catalog = Vending machine for infrastructure. Developers select from approved options; governance is built in. No AWS console access needed.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Service Catalog is equivalent to a self-service IT portal (like ServiceNow) where users request pre-approved infrastructure — maintaining governance while enabling developer agility."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between Amazon S3 server-side encryption options: SSE-S3, SSE-KMS, and SSE-C?","options":["They all use the same keys","SSE-S3 uses AWS-managed keys; SSE-KMS uses customer-managed KMS keys with audit trail; SSE-C uses customer-provided keys that AWS doesn't store","SSE-C is the cheapest option","SSE-S3 provides the most control"],"correct_answer":"SSE-S3 uses AWS-managed keys; SSE-KMS uses customer-managed KMS keys with audit trail; SSE-C uses customer-provided keys that AWS doesn't store","explanation":"SSE-S3: AWS manages keys entirely (simplest). SSE-KMS: Uses KMS keys you control with CloudTrail audit logging of key usage. SSE-C: You provide the encryption key with each request; AWS doesn't store it.","memory_technique":"SSE-S3 = AWS holds the key (easy). SSE-KMS = You control the key via KMS (auditable). SSE-C = You bring your own key (maximum control, most responsibility).","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"SSE-S3 is like provider-managed encryption; SSE-KMS is like using your own HSM-managed keys; SSE-C is like client-side encryption where you maintain full key custody."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a solution that automatically remediates security findings from GuardDuty. Which architecture achieves this?","options":["Manual review and remediation","GuardDuty → EventBridge → Lambda (automated remediation)","GuardDuty → SNS → email notification only","GuardDuty → CloudWatch Logs → manual analysis"],"correct_answer":"GuardDuty → EventBridge → Lambda (automated remediation)","explanation":"GuardDuty findings are automatically sent to EventBridge. EventBridge rules can trigger Lambda functions that perform automated remediation — such as isolating compromised instances, revoking IAM credentials, or blocking malicious IPs in WAF.","memory_technique":"GuardDuty detects → EventBridge routes → Lambda remediates. Automated security response — detect, decide, act. No human in the loop for known threats.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"This is equivalent to SOAR (Security Orchestration, Automation, and Response) — automatically responding to security alerts with predefined playbooks, reducing mean time to respond."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of AWS Lake Formation's governed tables?","options":["Tables that are governed by IAM policies only","Tables that support ACID transactions, automatic compaction, and row-level security in a data lake","Tables stored in a governed S3 bucket","Tables that require manual governance"],"correct_answer":"Tables that support ACID transactions, automatic compaction, and row-level security in a data lake","explanation":"Lake Formation governed tables bring database-like capabilities to data lakes: ACID transactions for concurrent reads/writes, automatic data compaction for query performance, and row/cell-level security for fine-grained access control.","memory_technique":"Governed tables = Database features in a data lake. ACID + compaction + row-level security. Best of both worlds.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Governed tables bridge the gap between data lakes and data warehouses — providing the governance and transactional capabilities of a database while maintaining the flexibility and cost of a data lake."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a solution where their on-premises applications can access AWS services using private IP addresses without internet connectivity. Which service enables this?","options":["AWS VPN","AWS Direct Connect with VPC Interface Endpoints (PrivateLink)","Internet Gateway","NAT Gateway"],"correct_answer":"AWS Direct Connect with VPC Interface Endpoints (PrivateLink)","explanation":"Direct Connect provides private connectivity from on-premises to AWS. VPC Interface Endpoints (powered by PrivateLink) provide private IP addresses for AWS services within the VPC. Combined, on-premises applications can access AWS services entirely over private networks.","memory_technique":"Direct Connect + PrivateLink = Fully private path. On-premises → Direct Connect → VPC → PrivateLink → AWS service. No internet anywhere in the chain.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"This architecture mirrors traditional private WAN connectivity to service providers — a dedicated circuit to the provider's network with private addressing, never touching the public internet."},
  {"question_text":"What is the AWS Well-Architected Framework's recommendation for implementing observability?","options":["Monitor only CPU and memory","Implement the three pillars of observability: metrics, logs, and traces across all application components","Monitor only application errors","Use a single monitoring tool for everything"],"correct_answer":"Implement the three pillars of observability: metrics, logs, and traces across all application components","explanation":"The Well-Architected Framework recommends implementing comprehensive observability through metrics (CloudWatch Metrics), logs (CloudWatch Logs), and distributed traces (X-Ray). Together they provide complete visibility into system behaviour.","memory_technique":"Three pillars of observability: Metrics (numbers), Logs (events), Traces (request paths). All three together = full visibility.","topic_area":"Cloud Concepts","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"The three pillars of observability map to traditional monitoring categories: performance monitoring (metrics), log management (logs), and application performance management (traces)."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a solution that allows them to run the same container workload across AWS, on-premises, and other clouds using a consistent management plane. Which service provides this?","options":["Amazon ECS","Amazon EKS Anywhere","AWS Fargate","AWS App Runner"],"correct_answer":"Amazon EKS Anywhere","explanation":"Amazon EKS Anywhere allows you to create and operate Kubernetes clusters on your own infrastructure using the same EKS management tools. It provides a consistent Kubernetes experience across AWS, on-premises, and edge environments.","memory_technique":"EKS Anywhere = EKS everywhere. Same Kubernetes management plane whether you're on AWS, in your data center, or at the edge.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"EKS Anywhere is equivalent to hybrid Kubernetes platforms like Red Hat OpenShift or Rancher — providing a consistent container orchestration layer across multiple environments."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of AWS Savings Plans utilisation and coverage reports?","options":["To show how much you've saved overall","To show what percentage of your eligible usage is covered by Savings Plans (coverage) and what percentage of your Savings Plans commitment is being used (utilisation)","To show Reserved Instance usage only","To forecast future savings"],"correct_answer":"To show what percentage of your eligible usage is covered by Savings Plans (coverage) and what percentage of your Savings Plans commitment is being used (utilisation)","explanation":"Coverage reports show what percentage of your eligible spend is covered by Savings Plans (higher = more savings). Utilisation reports show what percentage of your commitment is being used (lower = wasted commitment). Together they help optimise your Savings Plans portfolio.","memory_technique":"Coverage = How much of your bill is discounted. Utilisation = How much of your commitment is used. High coverage + high utilisation = optimal.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"These reports mirror enterprise licence management metrics — tracking licence utilisation (are you using what you bought?) and coverage (are all eligible workloads covered by discounts?)."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a solution that provides real-time fraud detection for financial transactions using ML without building custom models. Which AWS service is most appropriate?","options":["Amazon SageMaker","Amazon Fraud Detector","Amazon Comprehend","Amazon Rekognition"],"correct_answer":"Amazon Fraud Detector","explanation":"Amazon Fraud Detector is a fully managed service that uses ML to identify potentially fraudulent online activities. It uses your historical data to build custom fraud detection models without requiring ML expertise.","memory_technique":"Fraud Detector = ML-powered fraud cop. Trained on your data to spot fraudulent transactions — no ML expertise needed.","topic_area":"Technology","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Amazon Fraud Detector replaces custom fraud detection models and rules engines. It provides the same ML-based fraud scoring that financial institutions build internally, but as a managed service."},
  {"question_text":"What is the difference between AWS Budgets alerts and AWS Budgets Actions?","options":["They are the same","Alerts send notifications when thresholds are breached; Actions can automatically apply IAM policies or stop instances when thresholds are breached","Alerts stop instances; Actions send notifications","Actions are free; Alerts cost money"],"correct_answer":"Alerts send notifications when thresholds are breached; Actions can automatically apply IAM policies or stop instances when thresholds are breached","explanation":"Budget Alerts send notifications (email, SNS) when a threshold is approached or exceeded. Budget Actions go further — they can automatically apply restrictive IAM policies, stop EC2 instances, or stop RDS instances to prevent further spending.","memory_technique":"Alerts = Warning bell (notification only). Actions = Automatic brake (stops spending). Alerts inform; Actions enforce.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Alerts are like budget warning emails from finance; Actions are like automatic purchase order freezes when a department exceeds its budget — automated enforcement vs. manual notification."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a solution that provides automated compliance evidence collection for SOC 2 audits across multiple AWS accounts. Which service is most appropriate?","options":["AWS Config","AWS CloudTrail","AWS Audit Manager","AWS Security Hub"],"correct_answer":"AWS Audit Manager","explanation":"AWS Audit Manager continuously collects evidence from multiple AWS accounts and maps it to compliance frameworks like SOC 2, PCI DSS, and HIPAA. It automates evidence collection, organises it by control, and generates audit-ready reports.","memory_technique":"Audit Manager = Compliance evidence robot. Automatically collects and organises evidence for auditors — no more last-minute scrambling before an audit.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Audit Manager replaces manual evidence collection spreadsheets and GRC tools. It's equivalent to automated compliance platforms like Drata or Vanta — continuously collecting evidence mapped to compliance frameworks."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of AWS Graviton processors and when should you consider using them?","options":["They are GPUs for machine learning","ARM-based processors designed by AWS that provide up to 40% better price-performance than x86 for many workloads","They are only for HPC workloads","They are quantum computing processors"],"correct_answer":"ARM-based processors designed by AWS that provide up to 40% better price-performance than x86 for many workloads","explanation":"AWS Graviton processors are custom ARM-based chips designed by AWS. Graviton3 instances provide up to 40% better price-performance than comparable x86 instances for workloads like web servers, containerised microservices, and open-source databases.","memory_technique":"Graviton = AWS's own ARM chip. Better price-performance for most workloads. Same code (if it runs on Linux), lower cost.","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"Graviton represents the shift from x86 to ARM in data centers — similar to Apple's M-series transition. For compatible workloads, it provides significant cost savings without code changes."},
  {"question_text":"A company needs to implement a solution that provides centralised network security inspection for all traffic flowing between VPCs in their multi-account environment. Which architecture is most appropriate?","options":["Security Groups on each instance","AWS Network Firewall in a centralised inspection VPC with Transit Gateway routing","NACLs on each subnet","AWS WAF on each application"],"correct_answer":"AWS Network Firewall in a centralised inspection VPC with Transit Gateway routing","explanation":"A centralised inspection architecture uses Transit Gateway to route all inter-VPC traffic through a dedicated inspection VPC containing AWS Network Firewall. This provides consistent network security inspection without deploying firewalls in every VPC.","memory_technique":"Centralised inspection = All traffic flows through one checkpoint. Transit Gateway routes traffic → Inspection VPC with Network Firewall → destination. One firewall to inspect all.","topic_area":"Security and Compliance","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"This mirrors traditional hub-and-spoke network security architecture — all traffic flows through a centralised firewall cluster for inspection before reaching its destination."},
  {"question_text":"What is the purpose of AWS Savings Plans recommendations in Cost Explorer?","options":["To recommend which services to use","To analyse your historical usage patterns and recommend the optimal Savings Plans commitment to maximise savings","To recommend Reserved Instance purchases only","To recommend Spot Instance usage"],"correct_answer":"To analyse your historical usage patterns and recommend the optimal Savings Plans commitment to maximise savings","explanation":"Cost Explorer's Savings Plans recommendations analyse your past 7, 30, or 60 days of usage to recommend the optimal hourly commitment amount. It shows estimated savings, coverage, and the break-even point for different commitment levels.","memory_technique":"SP recommendations = Data-driven savings advice. AWS analyses your history and says 'commit $X/hour to save Y% — here's the math.'","topic_area":"Billing and Pricing","difficulty_level":5,"it_context_mapping":"SP recommendations are equivalent to enterprise procurement analysis — using historical consumption data to determine the optimal volume commitment for maximum discount."},
]

